1
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:03,763
Ooh, sorry Mr. Frost.

2
00:01:03,835 --> 00:01:05,359
I didn't mean to startle you.

3
00:01:05,437 --> 00:01:07,701
We're running a wee
bit late this morning.

4
00:01:07,772 --> 00:01:11,538
We overslept and Donald's
got a terrible migraine.

5
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:14,490
Nice sport this, isn't it?

6
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,868
I was thinking of
taking it up myself.

7
00:04:21,937 --> 00:04:25,839
Slow and gentle.

8
00:04:25,907 --> 00:04:27,670
Must get a lot of
thinking done, do you?

9
00:04:27,743 --> 00:04:30,371
If it's thinking you want,
try Open University.

10
00:04:30,445 --> 00:04:33,471
Competition this is.

11
00:04:33,548 --> 00:04:34,913
All right.

12
00:04:34,983 --> 00:04:38,942
I saw a bloke catch
a body in here once.

13
00:04:39,021 --> 00:04:42,616
About a year ago, it was.

14
00:04:42,691 --> 00:04:43,658
I don't know what it weighed,

15
00:04:43,725 --> 00:04:44,987
but it wasn't half a big one.

16
00:04:45,060 --> 00:04:46,618
Look, haven't you got
anything useful to do?

17
00:04:46,695 --> 00:04:49,721
You're frightening
the flaming fish.

18
00:04:49,798 --> 00:04:51,390
Sorry.

19
00:05:06,048 --> 00:05:07,913
Oi!

20
00:05:36,445 --> 00:05:38,242
Hi, Debs, just off?

21
00:05:38,313 --> 00:05:40,178
What's that, the
new (unintelligible)?

22
00:05:40,248 --> 00:05:41,613
You'd smell it if it was.

23
00:05:41,683 --> 00:05:44,083
Just a little something
to brighten my living room.

24
00:05:44,152 --> 00:05:45,779
How's the physio-therapy?

25
00:05:45,854 --> 00:05:46,843
I don't do physio.

26
00:05:46,922 --> 00:05:47,980
It's aroma therapy.

27
00:05:48,056 --> 00:05:49,284
And you know that very well.

28
00:05:49,358 --> 00:05:50,586
It's fine, thank you, Les.

29
00:05:50,659 --> 00:05:52,149
See you sometime.

30
00:05:52,227 --> 00:05:54,024
Hello, Shangri.

31
00:06:29,664 --> 00:06:32,428
Anything else you
care to say to us?

32
00:06:32,501 --> 00:06:35,163
No sir, you've been
most considerate.

33
00:06:35,237 --> 00:06:36,670
What about you,
Chief Constable?

34
00:06:36,738 --> 00:06:37,796
Nothing, chairman.

35
00:06:37,873 --> 00:06:41,536
I think the file tells us
everything we need to know.

36
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:44,306
Well, then thank you,
Superintendent Mullett.

37
00:06:44,379 --> 00:06:45,346
I have to say

38
00:06:45,414 --> 00:06:49,407
you've answered all our
questions very lucidly.

39
00:06:49,484 --> 00:06:52,385
If we should decide to recall
you for the final round,

40
00:06:52,454 --> 00:06:55,946
you'll be hearing from us
within the next seven days.

41
00:06:56,024 --> 00:06:57,355
Thank you.

42
00:07:10,472 --> 00:07:11,439
Glad to hear it, sir.

43
00:07:11,506 --> 00:07:13,235
Competition's weak too.

44
00:07:13,308 --> 00:07:15,037
One word in the ear though.

45
00:07:15,110 --> 00:07:16,441
Denton's time sheets.

46
00:07:16,511 --> 00:07:18,604
I'm informed they were
late again last month.

47
00:07:18,680 --> 00:07:19,908
It is very important

48
00:07:19,981 --> 00:07:22,745
to keep a tight ship
in the circumstances.

49
00:07:22,818 --> 00:07:25,309
Remember, performance
is the big buzzword now.

50
00:07:25,387 --> 00:07:27,014
Yes, I do know that, sir.

51
00:07:27,088 --> 00:07:29,215
How's Jack Frost, by the way?

52
00:07:29,291 --> 00:07:31,816
Awful, that young
Barnard's death.

53
00:07:31,893 --> 00:07:33,861
Must have been a
real blow for Jack.

54
00:07:33,929 --> 00:07:36,591
A lesser man would have
resigned from the force.

55
00:07:36,665 --> 00:07:37,495
Colonel,

56
00:07:37,566 --> 00:07:39,431
a word in your ear.

57
00:08:26,248 --> 00:08:27,943
(Knock on door)

58
00:08:30,185 --> 00:08:31,413
Come.

59
00:08:32,954 --> 00:08:34,649
DS Wallace, sir.

60
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:41,558
Ah, DS Wallace.

61
00:08:41,630 --> 00:08:42,824
Welcome back.

62
00:08:42,898 --> 00:08:43,990
Thank you, sir.

63
00:08:47,235 --> 00:08:48,497
How was the college?

64
00:08:48,570 --> 00:08:50,401
The course went
very well, sir.

65
00:08:50,472 --> 00:08:51,905
Ambition.

66
00:08:51,973 --> 00:08:53,873
It's a very fine thing.

67
00:08:53,942 --> 00:08:55,500
I like your new office.

68
00:08:55,577 --> 00:08:57,135
Yes, things have
changed a good deal

69
00:08:57,212 --> 00:08:58,372
since you were here last.

70
00:08:58,446 --> 00:08:59,606
For the better, I think.

71
00:08:59,681 --> 00:09:01,114
There's a modern
professional attitude

72
00:09:01,182 --> 00:09:02,911
right through the station.

73
00:09:02,984 --> 00:09:04,884
And you heard
about D.I. Frost?

74
00:09:04,953 --> 00:09:06,113
Yes, sir.

75
00:09:06,187 --> 00:09:08,985
Although I'm
surprised he resigned.

76
00:09:09,057 --> 00:09:10,752
Resigned?

77
00:09:10,825 --> 00:09:11,792
Who told you that?

78
00:09:11,860 --> 00:09:12,827
No, no.

79
00:09:12,894 --> 00:09:16,990
The fact is I granted him
extended compassionate leave.

80
00:09:17,065 --> 00:09:20,501
The death of DS Barnard
hit him particularly hard.

81
00:09:20,569 --> 00:09:23,902
He always was an
emotional officer.

82
00:09:23,972 --> 00:09:25,997
Me too sir.

83
00:09:26,074 --> 00:09:28,406
I was very close to him once.

84
00:09:28,476 --> 00:09:30,171
What, Frost?

85
00:09:30,245 --> 00:09:32,805
I meant DS Barnard.

86
00:09:32,881 --> 00:09:35,145
Really?

87
00:09:35,216 --> 00:09:36,478
The man at the top

88
00:09:36,551 --> 00:09:38,348
is always last to
know about these things.

89
00:09:38,420 --> 00:09:41,787
Does that mean Inspector
Frost is coming back, sir?

90
00:09:41,856 --> 00:09:45,257
Well, better assume not.

91
00:09:45,327 --> 00:09:47,921
When I...

92
00:09:47,996 --> 00:09:49,156
The fact is, sergeant,

93
00:09:49,230 --> 00:09:52,165
his leave has put me
in an awkward position.

94
00:09:52,233 --> 00:09:53,063
Well, you knew him,

95
00:09:53,134 --> 00:09:54,431
you know what
I'm talking about.

96
00:09:54,502 --> 00:09:56,436
Frankly he left the
place a perfect tip.

97
00:09:56,504 --> 00:09:57,528
Always was his way.

98
00:09:57,606 --> 00:10:00,131
Well, it's no longer
our way, sergeant.

99
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:01,903
First job, I want you
to take over his office,

100
00:10:01,977 --> 00:10:02,909
working to me.

101
00:10:02,978 --> 00:10:03,967
Sort it all out.

102
00:10:04,045 --> 00:10:05,034
Just go through everything.

103
00:10:05,113 --> 00:10:06,171
Unfinished cases,

104
00:10:06,247 --> 00:10:07,578
untranscribed
interviews, notebooks.

105
00:10:07,649 --> 00:10:09,082
Staff recharges,
time sheets.

106
00:10:09,150 --> 00:10:11,050
The lot.

107
00:10:11,119 --> 00:10:12,416
No witch-hunt mind,

108
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:17,356
but I need a very tight ship

109
00:10:17,425 --> 00:10:20,519
over the next
couple of weeks.

110
00:10:20,595 --> 00:10:23,189
Inspection, sir?

111
00:10:23,264 --> 00:10:27,257
As I said, ambition,

112
00:10:27,335 --> 00:10:29,360
it's a very fine thing.

113
00:10:37,679 --> 00:10:41,046
(Phone rings)

114
00:10:56,665 --> 00:10:58,030
Hello.

115
00:10:58,099 --> 00:11:02,035
Oh, it's you, how did I guess.

116
00:11:02,103 --> 00:11:02,967
No, not this one.

117
00:11:03,038 --> 00:11:05,506
Not this time.

118
00:11:05,573 --> 00:11:08,770
Yes, I know that's what
we've done in the past.

119
00:11:08,843 --> 00:11:10,743
Up yours too.

120
00:11:50,618 --> 00:11:51,312
See you tomorrow,

121
00:11:51,386 --> 00:11:52,751
thank you.

122
00:12:48,409 --> 00:12:50,104
Hi, anybody home?

123
00:12:50,178 --> 00:12:52,112
Course not, why ask?

124
00:13:26,481 --> 00:13:27,470
Hazel.

125
00:13:27,549 --> 00:13:28,675
Hello, George.

126
00:13:28,750 --> 00:13:31,014
It's good to see you again.

127
00:13:31,085 --> 00:13:34,680
Well, Mullett's given you
Jack's old office I see.

128
00:13:34,756 --> 00:13:36,485
It could do with
a perfume spray.

129
00:13:36,558 --> 00:13:38,822
He's asked me to go
through his paperwork.

130
00:13:38,893 --> 00:13:41,225
Rather you than me.

131
00:13:41,296 --> 00:13:42,388
Did you hear about Jack?

132
00:13:42,463 --> 00:13:43,225
Yeh?

133
00:13:43,298 --> 00:13:44,856
Mullett said he's on
compassionate leave.

134
00:13:44,933 --> 00:13:46,423
Crafty old devil.

135
00:13:46,501 --> 00:13:48,162
No, Jack resigned.

136
00:13:48,236 --> 00:13:49,464
But Mullett
doesn't want to upset

137
00:13:49,537 --> 00:13:50,731
the Chief Constable.

138
00:13:50,805 --> 00:13:52,864
Jack always was his
favorite copper.

139
00:13:52,941 --> 00:13:55,501
Yeah, I remember.

140
00:13:55,577 --> 00:13:57,067
What's he doing now?

141
00:13:57,145 --> 00:13:58,635
Wandering round Denton

142
00:13:58,713 --> 00:14:01,079
dreaming he's free at last.

143
00:14:14,062 --> 00:14:15,552
Mr. Frost.

144
00:14:15,630 --> 00:14:16,995
Nice day?

145
00:14:17,065 --> 00:14:18,555
Is it?

146
00:14:18,633 --> 00:14:21,397
I meant yours.

147
00:14:21,469 --> 00:14:23,801
No, not really, Brian.

148
00:14:23,872 --> 00:14:25,737
No, not really.

149
00:14:25,807 --> 00:14:28,674
Donald's doing
eggs Benedict tonight.

150
00:14:28,743 --> 00:14:30,574
One of his specialties.

151
00:14:30,645 --> 00:14:32,510
He should really
be in a restaurant.

152
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:34,980
Yeah.

153
00:14:35,049 --> 00:14:36,778
Yes all right, Brian.

154
00:14:36,851 --> 00:14:38,478
All right, thanks.

155
00:15:11,786 --> 00:15:13,219
Shangri?

156
00:15:15,156 --> 00:15:16,384
Shangri?

157
00:15:17,592 --> 00:15:19,560
Puss, puss.

158
00:15:19,627 --> 00:15:21,458
Puss.

159
00:15:32,473 --> 00:15:33,997
Shangri.

160
00:15:34,075 --> 00:15:35,133
Hello.

161
00:15:36,144 --> 00:15:38,442
Good girl.

162
00:15:38,513 --> 00:15:40,037
Do you want some dinner?

163
00:15:47,822 --> 00:15:49,414
Ah, good evening, Norman.

164
00:15:49,490 --> 00:15:50,422
Good evening.

165
00:15:50,491 --> 00:15:51,458
Quite a coup for Denton.

166
00:15:51,526 --> 00:15:52,550
The Lydian Quartet.

167
00:15:52,627 --> 00:15:54,492
Yes, yes, absolutely.

168
00:15:59,033 --> 00:16:00,295
Well, well.

169
00:16:00,368 --> 00:16:02,063
The Bill goes classical?

170
00:16:02,136 --> 00:16:03,034
I'm sorry?

171
00:16:03,104 --> 00:16:06,665
I take it we are
off duty for once?

172
00:16:06,741 --> 00:16:08,038
You failed to recognize me

173
00:16:08,109 --> 00:16:09,576
without my mortuary gown.

174
00:16:09,644 --> 00:16:10,576
Derek Simpkins,

175
00:16:10,645 --> 00:16:12,613
your friendly
neighborhood pathologist.

176
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:14,910
Yes, of course.

177
00:16:14,983 --> 00:16:16,211
You know, Superintendent,

178
00:16:16,284 --> 00:16:17,342
I never had you down

179
00:16:17,418 --> 00:16:19,318
for a lover of serious music.

180
00:16:19,387 --> 00:16:20,513
Ah, well I'm not really.

181
00:16:20,588 --> 00:16:22,215
It's my wife Elsbeth.

182
00:16:22,290 --> 00:16:24,121
She belongs to a small
music club you know.

183
00:16:24,192 --> 00:16:26,057
Ah, there you are Diana.

184
00:16:26,127 --> 00:16:28,595
Remember
Superintendent Mullett?

185
00:16:28,663 --> 00:16:31,655
Yes, of course, good
evening Superintendent.

186
00:16:31,733 --> 00:16:32,495
Are you?

187
00:16:32,567 --> 00:16:34,398
Waiting for my wife, yes.

188
00:16:34,469 --> 00:16:35,731
You'll have a long
wait, I'm afraid.

189
00:16:35,803 --> 00:16:37,168
In that case let's get seated.

190
00:16:37,238 --> 00:16:39,900
I can't bear to
have music interrupted.

191
00:16:47,548 --> 00:16:48,879
You're not still at it?

192
00:16:48,950 --> 00:16:50,679
This will take ages.

193
00:16:50,752 --> 00:16:52,652
I don't think Jack ever filed
a single thing in his life.

194
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:53,846
No, he thought
the filing cabinet

195
00:16:53,921 --> 00:16:56,082
was the same as the fridge.

196
00:16:56,157 --> 00:16:58,182
Have you checked his computer?

197
00:16:58,259 --> 00:16:59,658
His computer!

198
00:17:02,764 --> 00:17:06,165
Have you found anything
on the Black Farm Murder?

199
00:17:06,234 --> 00:17:07,030
Black Farm?

200
00:17:07,101 --> 00:17:08,432
Yeah, take a look at that.

201
00:17:08,503 --> 00:17:10,095
It happened about
eight years ago.

202
00:17:10,171 --> 00:17:11,695
A rich farmer, Jonathan Dale

203
00:17:11,773 --> 00:17:13,638
was murdered
just outside Denton.

204
00:17:13,708 --> 00:17:15,539
A tealeaf called
Branson went down for it,

205
00:17:15,610 --> 00:17:17,134
died in prison last year.

206
00:17:17,211 --> 00:17:20,271
Now this new bloke says
he pulled the trigger.

207
00:17:20,348 --> 00:17:20,973
One of Jack's?

208
00:17:21,049 --> 00:17:21,845
Oh, yeah.

209
00:17:21,916 --> 00:17:23,474
Who fancies a nice night out?

210
00:17:23,551 --> 00:17:24,347
Who wouldn't?

211
00:17:24,419 --> 00:17:26,387
Suspicious death,
Riverside Apartments.

212
00:17:26,454 --> 00:17:27,819
Jordan's already down there.

213
00:17:27,889 --> 00:17:28,913
Yeah.

214
00:17:28,990 --> 00:17:30,150
Well, off you go.

215
00:17:30,224 --> 00:17:32,556
It's time for your first solo.

216
00:18:18,172 --> 00:18:19,298
It's this room here.

217
00:18:20,108 --> 00:18:21,735
Hello, Chris. what is it then?

218
00:18:21,809 --> 00:18:22,867
One dead male,

219
00:18:22,944 --> 00:18:24,275
probable suicide.

220
00:18:24,345 --> 00:18:27,178
The girl from next
door Leonie Viner,

221
00:18:27,248 --> 00:18:29,113
found him when she
looked in to feed the cat.

222
00:18:29,183 --> 00:18:31,048
That's her, through there.

223
00:18:31,119 --> 00:18:32,211
You did put someone with her?

224
00:18:32,286 --> 00:18:34,277
Yeah, a WPC.

225
00:18:34,355 --> 00:18:36,084
Yes, of course, right.

226
00:18:36,157 --> 00:18:37,818
Better show me then.

227
00:18:37,892 --> 00:18:38,688
Right.

228
00:18:38,759 --> 00:18:39,953
Through here.

229
00:18:40,928 --> 00:18:43,897
Leonie called a
doctor, lives upstairs.

230
00:18:43,965 --> 00:18:46,024
He said he'd been
dead an hour maybe two.

231
00:19:00,348 --> 00:19:01,815
Got an ident yet?

232
00:19:01,883 --> 00:19:04,511
Yeah, she says
he's the tenant,

233
00:19:04,585 --> 00:19:06,553
Lester Bryce-Jones.

234
00:19:06,621 --> 00:19:07,645
He lived alone,

235
00:19:07,722 --> 00:19:09,587
except for a
large bunch of keys,

236
00:19:09,657 --> 00:19:11,420
some nice pictures,

237
00:19:11,492 --> 00:19:12,686
and his cat.

238
00:19:12,760 --> 00:19:14,352
Leonie feeds it sometimes.

239
00:19:14,428 --> 00:19:15,520
She's very distressed,

240
00:19:15,596 --> 00:19:17,757
her mother's not home yet.

241
00:19:18,866 --> 00:19:20,925
You said suicide?

242
00:19:21,002 --> 00:19:22,094
He'd been drinking,

243
00:19:22,170 --> 00:19:24,104
taking pills.

244
00:19:24,172 --> 00:19:26,504
Couldn't it have been sexual?

245
00:19:26,574 --> 00:19:27,836
No idea, darling.

246
00:19:27,909 --> 00:19:29,536
I'm a married man.

247
00:19:32,780 --> 00:19:34,179
What's this?

248
00:19:39,554 --> 00:19:41,419
A doctor?

249
00:20:01,909 --> 00:20:05,310
(Beeper)

250
00:20:19,427 --> 00:20:20,587
Duty calls.

251
00:20:20,661 --> 00:20:22,424
Yours probably!

252
00:20:33,474 --> 00:20:37,240
You could have a four
letter word ending in UCK.

253
00:20:40,781 --> 00:20:42,112
There you are.

254
00:20:42,183 --> 00:20:43,172
Right, go on.

255
00:20:43,251 --> 00:20:44,149
How many's that then?

256
00:20:44,218 --> 00:20:45,344
You've got a
triple letter there,

257
00:20:45,419 --> 00:20:48,547
so that makes twenty.

258
00:20:48,623 --> 00:20:50,750
Some people have all the uck.

259
00:20:53,494 --> 00:20:54,756
Let's have another glass.

260
00:20:58,399 --> 00:21:00,230
Ah, we're dry.

261
00:21:00,301 --> 00:21:02,701
I'll go and ask Donald
for another bottle.

262
00:21:02,770 --> 00:21:04,567
He makes a nice
selection, don't you think?

263
00:21:04,639 --> 00:21:06,072
Uhu.

264
00:21:06,140 --> 00:21:08,074
Or would you prefer
a cup of Horlicks?

265
00:21:08,142 --> 00:21:10,167
No no, I'll stick with this.

266
00:21:11,312 --> 00:21:12,540
DS Wallace,
thank you for coming.

267
00:21:12,613 --> 00:21:13,978
You are aware I was
at a chamber concert?

268
00:21:14,048 --> 00:21:14,742
Sorry.

269
00:21:14,815 --> 00:21:15,747
Not seen you before.

270
00:21:15,816 --> 00:21:16,714
New, are you?

271
00:21:16,784 --> 00:21:17,773
You have,
but you won't remember.

272
00:21:17,852 --> 00:21:18,910
I used to be in uniform.

273
00:21:18,986 --> 00:21:19,918
Didn't they tell you?

274
00:21:19,987 --> 00:21:22,148
I'm a pathologist,
not a police doctor.

275
00:21:22,223 --> 00:21:23,349
I don't attend crime scenes,

276
00:21:23,424 --> 00:21:25,392
I conduct autopsies
and forensic research.

277
00:21:25,459 --> 00:21:27,256
I thought a pathologist
ought to be on scene.

278
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:28,352
Did you really?

279
00:21:28,429 --> 00:21:29,418
I'm not sure it's suicide.

280
00:21:29,497 --> 00:21:30,361
There are drugs around,

281
00:21:30,431 --> 00:21:31,864
possibly some
hospital connection.

282
00:21:31,932 --> 00:21:34,093
Oh well, get out
your notebook, Diana.

283
00:21:34,168 --> 00:21:37,001
I don't generally take
it to concerts, Doctor.

284
00:21:37,071 --> 00:21:38,629
Will this do?

285
00:21:38,706 --> 00:21:42,142
Wouldn't have a stethoscope
in there as well, would you?

286
00:21:42,209 --> 00:21:43,767
In here I suppose?

287
00:21:47,515 --> 00:21:49,073
Interesting.

288
00:21:52,420 --> 00:21:53,944
Aah.

289
00:21:54,789 --> 00:21:57,883
Over here, sir.

290
00:21:57,958 --> 00:21:59,084
What's this then?

291
00:21:59,160 --> 00:22:01,424
Our art collector?

292
00:22:01,495 --> 00:22:03,725
And you left him
hanging just for me.

293
00:22:03,798 --> 00:22:06,028
Mr. Lester Bryce-Jones.

294
00:22:06,100 --> 00:22:07,727
I presume a doctor
looked at him already?

295
00:22:07,802 --> 00:22:09,793
Yes, sir, said he was dead.

296
00:22:09,870 --> 00:22:12,430
Brilliant, can't
be faulted, can he?

297
00:22:12,506 --> 00:22:14,098
What of, though?

298
00:22:14,175 --> 00:22:15,574
He thought hanging, sir.

299
00:22:15,643 --> 00:22:17,907
We'll decide that
at the post-mortem.

300
00:22:17,978 --> 00:22:21,345
But I see why you
need a pathologist.

301
00:22:21,415 --> 00:22:22,780
Anything else here
that might be lethal?

302
00:22:22,850 --> 00:22:24,647
He seems to have taken drugs.

303
00:22:24,719 --> 00:22:25,811
There are more
in the bathroom.

304
00:22:25,886 --> 00:22:28,878
These aren't drugs,
these are medicines.

305
00:22:28,956 --> 00:22:30,787
Come here, Diana, will you?

306
00:22:35,463 --> 00:22:38,899
What's all this
on his eyelids?

307
00:22:38,966 --> 00:22:41,366
That's mascara, doctor.

308
00:22:56,484 --> 00:22:57,849
What's going on?

309
00:23:09,463 --> 00:23:11,658
Darling are you all right?

310
00:23:11,732 --> 00:23:13,791
You should have called me.

311
00:23:13,868 --> 00:23:15,392
You don't like me to.

312
00:23:15,469 --> 00:23:16,731
Mrs. Viner?

313
00:23:16,804 --> 00:23:18,465
Let me tell you, your
daughter's been brilliant.

314
00:23:18,539 --> 00:23:19,403
She called the doctor.

315
00:23:19,473 --> 00:23:20,235
And the police.

316
00:23:20,307 --> 00:23:22,400
I know she's
brilliant, thank you.

317
00:23:22,476 --> 00:23:23,636
Why did you go in there?

318
00:23:23,711 --> 00:23:24,769
To feed Shangri,

319
00:23:24,845 --> 00:23:27,473
I thought he was out.

320
00:23:27,548 --> 00:23:29,243
Anyway, what happened?

321
00:23:29,316 --> 00:23:30,374
I saw him in the hall earlier.

322
00:23:30,451 --> 00:23:31,918
He seemed fine.

323
00:23:31,986 --> 00:23:33,248
Why did he do it?

324
00:23:33,320 --> 00:23:34,218
Kill himself?

325
00:23:34,288 --> 00:23:36,256
We don't know that
he did, Mrs. Viner.

326
00:23:36,323 --> 00:23:37,654
What else then?

327
00:23:37,725 --> 00:23:39,750
I mean, surely nobody
would want to murder Les.

328
00:23:39,827 --> 00:23:42,057
You knew him quite well then?

329
00:23:42,129 --> 00:23:44,029
We need a formal
identification.

330
00:23:44,098 --> 00:23:44,928
Oh no, no, no.

331
00:23:44,999 --> 00:23:45,829
I didn't know him.

332
00:23:45,900 --> 00:23:47,265
Not really.

333
00:23:47,334 --> 00:23:48,767
He must have
relatives somewhere.

334
00:23:48,836 --> 00:23:49,768
Do you know where?

335
00:23:49,837 --> 00:23:50,861
No, I don't know where.

336
00:23:50,938 --> 00:23:52,405
I don't know
anything about him.

337
00:23:52,473 --> 00:23:53,963
He'd only lived there a year.

338
00:23:54,041 --> 00:23:54,905
Now go away, please,

339
00:23:54,975 --> 00:23:56,704
I want to look
after my daughter.

340
00:23:56,777 --> 00:23:58,108
Leonie, I'm sorry,

341
00:23:58,179 --> 00:23:59,737
we're going to have to
talk to you again tomorrow,

342
00:23:59,814 --> 00:24:01,304
as a witness.

343
00:24:01,382 --> 00:24:02,440
Will you be all right tonight?

344
00:24:02,516 --> 00:24:03,813
Of course she will,

345
00:24:03,884 --> 00:24:06,045
now please go.

346
00:24:06,120 --> 00:24:08,020
Ssh, it's all right,
it's all right.

347
00:24:09,824 --> 00:24:11,416
There we go, Mr. Frost.

348
00:24:11,492 --> 00:24:13,722
Donald says enjoy.

349
00:24:13,794 --> 00:24:15,625
In that case I will
Brian, thank you.

350
00:24:15,696 --> 00:24:17,687
You should really
try muesli sometimes.

351
00:24:17,765 --> 00:24:19,858
It's a lot better
for the bowels.

352
00:24:19,934 --> 00:24:22,198
Oh, I nearly forgot.

353
00:24:22,269 --> 00:24:22,963
Letter for you.

354
00:24:23,037 --> 00:24:24,402
Oh, right.

355
00:24:36,183 --> 00:24:37,275
Well, blow me.

356
00:24:37,351 --> 00:24:38,545
Good news, is it?

357
00:24:38,619 --> 00:24:40,849
Granny died and left
you a massive fortune?

358
00:24:40,921 --> 00:24:42,115
Well, very nearly.

359
00:24:42,189 --> 00:24:44,316
About a year ago
I burnt my house down

360
00:24:44,391 --> 00:24:47,019
because I wasn't paying due
care and attention, was I?

361
00:24:47,094 --> 00:24:49,426
So half a lifetime,
you know, went up in smoke.

362
00:24:49,497 --> 00:24:50,964
Doesn't sound like
very good news to me.

363
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:53,431
Ah, but I was insured.

364
00:24:53,501 --> 00:24:54,763
God knows how because

365
00:24:54,835 --> 00:24:57,429
I could never remember
sensible things like that.

366
00:24:57,505 --> 00:24:59,871
"...Iike to advise you the
process of refurbishment

367
00:24:59,940 --> 00:25:01,464
is complete and your property

368
00:25:01,542 --> 00:25:04,170
will shortly be available
for reoccupation... "

369
00:25:04,245 --> 00:25:05,644
Oh, Mr. Frost.

370
00:25:05,713 --> 00:25:07,908
I'd say that calls
for a celebration.

371
00:25:07,982 --> 00:25:09,449
So do I.

372
00:25:09,517 --> 00:25:11,576
Let's have some fried bread?

373
00:25:11,652 --> 00:25:15,088
I really wouldn't like to
be your stomach, Mr. Frost.

374
00:25:15,155 --> 00:25:18,522
Donald, Mr. Frost
wants some fried bread!

375
00:25:21,428 --> 00:25:22,861
Why?

376
00:25:22,930 --> 00:25:24,454
Why was the
Black Farm murder file

377
00:25:24,532 --> 00:25:27,000
removed from the records?

378
00:25:27,067 --> 00:25:28,398
No idea, sir.

379
00:25:28,469 --> 00:25:30,300
It must have been
for fresh inquiries.

380
00:25:30,371 --> 00:25:31,099
Well, who took it?

381
00:25:31,171 --> 00:25:32,763
Why wasn't it signed for?

382
00:25:32,840 --> 00:25:34,137
I can't imagine, sir.

383
00:25:34,208 --> 00:25:37,109
This is a disciplinary matter.

384
00:25:37,177 --> 00:25:39,008
I've called a press conference
on the Black Farm Murder

385
00:25:39,079 --> 00:25:40,410
in an hour's time.

386
00:25:40,481 --> 00:25:43,507
Somehow I assumed
I'd have the file with me.

387
00:25:43,584 --> 00:25:44,881
Find DS Wallace.

388
00:25:44,952 --> 00:25:46,442
She's on a case, sir.

389
00:25:46,520 --> 00:25:49,853
Dead male, Riverside
Apartments, possible murder.

390
00:25:49,924 --> 00:25:51,858
Isn't it all on the computer?

391
00:25:51,926 --> 00:25:53,359
This was eight
years ago, Toolan.

392
00:25:53,427 --> 00:25:55,895
Before we had computers,
if you remember.

393
00:25:55,963 --> 00:25:58,090
Yes, I do remember, sir.

394
00:25:58,165 --> 00:25:59,860
Sergeant, come here.

395
00:26:04,939 --> 00:26:07,305
I need that file at once.

396
00:26:07,374 --> 00:26:11,504
Now do I have to start
an official investigation?

397
00:26:11,579 --> 00:26:13,137
Very well, sir.

398
00:26:13,213 --> 00:26:15,579
You'd better come and see.

399
00:26:25,826 --> 00:26:27,088
And what's that?

400
00:26:29,029 --> 00:26:33,659
Well, that must be one of
Jack's little jokes, sir.

401
00:26:33,734 --> 00:26:34,894
It's here.

402
00:26:34,969 --> 00:26:36,402
Ah, at least it hasn't
left the building.

403
00:26:36,470 --> 00:26:38,267
Well, you'd better
look inside, sir.

404
00:26:41,942 --> 00:26:43,466
I see.

405
00:26:43,544 --> 00:26:45,478
Is that another
of Jack's little jokes?

406
00:26:45,546 --> 00:26:47,207
Well, he must have taken
the stuff home with him.

407
00:26:47,281 --> 00:26:48,839
Well it's totally irregular.

408
00:26:48,916 --> 00:26:50,508
Yes it is sir.

409
00:26:50,584 --> 00:26:52,313
But I expect he
meant to bring it back

410
00:26:52,386 --> 00:26:55,378
when he returned from his
compassionate leave, sir.

411
00:27:06,834 --> 00:27:08,028
It's not the only one, is it?

412
00:27:08,102 --> 00:27:10,070
Jack liked to keep
things in his head.

413
00:27:10,137 --> 00:27:11,434
Right that does it.

414
00:27:11,505 --> 00:27:12,267
I want his head

415
00:27:12,339 --> 00:27:13,670
and I want it on the block.

416
00:27:13,741 --> 00:27:14,639
Find him, bring him to me.

417
00:27:14,708 --> 00:27:15,538
And that file.

418
00:27:15,609 --> 00:27:17,304
I'm not quite sure
where he's living, sir.

419
00:27:17,378 --> 00:27:18,970
Then start a search for him.

420
00:27:19,046 --> 00:27:20,035
Arrest him if necessary.

421
00:27:20,114 --> 00:27:21,012
Arrest him?

422
00:27:21,081 --> 00:27:21,843
Yes.

423
00:27:21,915 --> 00:27:23,473
He's broken procedural rules.

424
00:27:23,550 --> 00:27:25,177
He's impeding
an urgent inquiry.

425
00:27:25,252 --> 00:27:27,618
He's bringing the
force into disrepute.

426
00:27:27,688 --> 00:27:28,450
You heard me.

427
00:27:28,522 --> 00:27:30,012
Arrest him!

428
00:27:42,136 --> 00:27:42,864
Mr. Frost.

429
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:33,625
Hello there.

430
00:27:33,701 --> 00:27:34,224
Hi.

431
00:27:34,302 --> 00:27:35,462
Hi.

432
00:27:35,536 --> 00:27:36,264
Here we are.

433
00:27:36,337 --> 00:27:38,168
All ready for inspection.

434
00:27:38,239 --> 00:27:39,672
Yes, It's nice.

435
00:27:39,741 --> 00:27:40,867
Very very nice.

436
00:27:40,942 --> 00:27:42,375
You'll be pleased
to have it back.

437
00:27:42,443 --> 00:27:44,570
After all,
home is always home.

438
00:27:44,645 --> 00:27:45,976
Full of memories.

439
00:27:46,047 --> 00:27:47,105
Family.

440
00:27:47,181 --> 00:27:49,012
You never forget, do you?

441
00:27:49,083 --> 00:27:50,846
No, I know what you mean.

442
00:27:50,918 --> 00:27:53,011
We've restored most
fixtures and fittings

443
00:27:53,087 --> 00:27:54,577
and we're willing to
pay a reasonable sum

444
00:27:54,655 --> 00:27:55,622
for furniture replacement.

445
00:27:55,690 --> 00:27:56,622
That's very good.

446
00:27:56,691 --> 00:27:57,715
Shall we look around?

447
00:27:57,792 --> 00:28:00,556
I wonder, if you'd mind.

448
00:28:00,628 --> 00:28:02,789
I like to look
around on my own.

449
00:28:02,864 --> 00:28:05,628
Yeah, sure.

450
00:28:05,700 --> 00:28:06,530
It's all yours.

451
00:28:06,601 --> 00:28:08,364
Oh, thank you.

452
00:28:08,436 --> 00:28:09,562
My pleasure.

453
00:28:09,637 --> 00:28:10,365
Bye now.

454
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:11,598
Goodbye.

455
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:08,092
Looks like one of ours.

456
00:29:08,168 --> 00:29:09,965
Certainly has
our laundry mark.

457
00:29:10,037 --> 00:29:11,902
But you can't tell
who it belongs to?

458
00:29:11,972 --> 00:29:13,303
One of the doctors perhaps?

459
00:29:13,374 --> 00:29:14,102
Doctor?

460
00:29:14,174 --> 00:29:15,072
No.

461
00:29:15,142 --> 00:29:16,905
More likely
one of the porters.

462
00:29:16,977 --> 00:29:18,535
A porter?

463
00:29:18,612 --> 00:29:19,874
How much would he earn?

464
00:29:19,947 --> 00:29:21,073
Working all hours?

465
00:29:21,148 --> 00:29:22,740
Say a thousand a month.

466
00:29:22,816 --> 00:29:24,113
Not a lot is it?

467
00:29:24,184 --> 00:29:25,583
If you want a lot of anything,

468
00:29:25,652 --> 00:29:27,677
you don't work for the NHS.

469
00:29:27,755 --> 00:29:30,417
Anyway these days it's
nothing to do with us.

470
00:29:30,491 --> 00:29:32,550
It's a privatized service.

471
00:29:32,626 --> 00:29:35,424
All to do with
the internal market.

472
00:29:35,496 --> 00:29:36,929
You'd best talk
to the contractors.

473
00:29:36,997 --> 00:29:39,625
They might be
able to help you.

474
00:29:39,700 --> 00:29:41,895
They're in the High Street.

475
00:29:41,969 --> 00:29:43,095
Thank you.

476
00:29:52,413 --> 00:29:53,744
It's very comfortable
isn't it, sir.

477
00:29:53,814 --> 00:29:54,803
Ideal for the study.

478
00:29:54,882 --> 00:29:55,746
Yes, yes.

479
00:29:55,816 --> 00:29:57,283
Very pricey though, I bet.

480
00:29:57,351 --> 00:29:59,012
It is genuine cowhide though.

481
00:29:59,086 --> 00:29:59,984
Ah, is it?

482
00:30:00,053 --> 00:30:02,647
all right, well,
I don't think so.

483
00:30:02,723 --> 00:30:05,954
Well, I don't think
my insurance company
will stretch to it.

484
00:30:06,026 --> 00:30:08,324
They're a bit
worried about BSE.

485
00:30:08,395 --> 00:30:09,293
Well, if there's a problem,

486
00:30:09,363 --> 00:30:10,660
we can arrange a
year before payment,

487
00:30:10,731 --> 00:30:11,959
or no percent finance...

488
00:30:24,545 --> 00:30:26,342
No joy, sorry.

489
00:30:26,413 --> 00:30:28,813
We never employed
a Lester Bryce-Jones.

490
00:30:28,882 --> 00:30:30,281
Do you recognize him?

491
00:30:32,719 --> 00:30:34,653
Don't think so.

492
00:30:34,721 --> 00:30:36,416
Nice boy though.

493
00:30:36,490 --> 00:30:38,185
He isn't now.

494
00:30:39,293 --> 00:30:40,521
When you employ people,

495
00:30:40,594 --> 00:30:42,425
do you check
their drugs record?

496
00:30:42,496 --> 00:30:43,485
If they'd been busted

497
00:30:43,564 --> 00:30:45,191
we wouldn't have hired them.

498
00:30:45,265 --> 00:30:47,290
How would you know?

499
00:30:47,367 --> 00:30:49,562
If they put it on a form?

500
00:30:49,636 --> 00:30:51,695
Can I see a form?

501
00:30:56,176 --> 00:30:57,575
(Car horn)

502
00:31:03,851 --> 00:31:04,840
Mr. Frost?

503
00:31:04,918 --> 00:31:06,180
Yes?

504
00:31:06,253 --> 00:31:07,618
Can you come with us, please?

505
00:31:07,688 --> 00:31:08,882
Do what?

506
00:31:08,956 --> 00:31:10,856
Mr. Mulletts orders sir.

507
00:31:10,924 --> 00:31:12,414
You are joking?

508
00:31:12,493 --> 00:31:14,324
Look, all right!

509
00:31:14,394 --> 00:31:16,521
You're going to
be in big trouble!

510
00:31:16,597 --> 00:31:19,862
I'll tell ya,
(unintelligible).

511
00:31:19,933 --> 00:31:22,163
All right I can
manage, thank you!

512
00:31:28,642 --> 00:31:29,370
Right.

513
00:31:29,443 --> 00:31:31,035
Good morning.

514
00:31:31,111 --> 00:31:33,807
Thank you for coming.

515
00:31:33,881 --> 00:31:35,712
Now I've called
this conference

516
00:31:35,782 --> 00:31:37,340
in view of the
recent press story

517
00:31:37,417 --> 00:31:40,045
about the Black Farm Murder.

518
00:31:40,120 --> 00:31:42,418
It may seem that there's
been a new development

519
00:31:42,489 --> 00:31:43,581
and that we...

520
00:31:43,657 --> 00:31:45,887
Jailed the wrong man.

521
00:31:45,959 --> 00:31:47,722
There's no evidence
of that Mr. Longford.

522
00:31:47,794 --> 00:31:49,125
A man was tried and convicted

523
00:31:49,196 --> 00:31:51,460
after a thorough investigation
by a senior officer.

524
00:31:51,532 --> 00:31:52,396
Jack Frost?

525
00:31:52,466 --> 00:31:53,490
Yes.

526
00:31:53,567 --> 00:31:57,333
So this confession in
Spain by Mr. Ferdie Giggs,

527
00:31:57,404 --> 00:31:59,201
you don't recognize
it as genuine?

528
00:31:59,273 --> 00:32:01,138
That is an
uncorroborated interview

529
00:32:01,208 --> 00:32:03,005
given by a foreign journalist

530
00:32:03,076 --> 00:32:04,839
with someone we don't know.

531
00:32:04,912 --> 00:32:06,470
You don't know him?

532
00:32:06,547 --> 00:32:09,107
But he was interviewed
as a suspect at
the time, wasn't he?

533
00:32:09,182 --> 00:32:12,640
By Detective
Inspector Frost.

534
00:32:12,719 --> 00:32:14,152
As far as we are aware,

535
00:32:14,221 --> 00:32:16,689
he was never seriously
considered as a suspect.

536
00:32:16,757 --> 00:32:19,282
He claims he was at
the scene of the crime.

537
00:32:19,359 --> 00:32:20,155
Does he?

538
00:32:20,227 --> 00:32:23,196
He'd have to be, if he did it.

539
00:32:23,263 --> 00:32:24,821
What do police records show?

540
00:32:24,898 --> 00:32:26,388
Mr. Giggs' statement
will be looked into

541
00:32:26,466 --> 00:32:28,457
and any necessary
action taken.

542
00:32:28,535 --> 00:32:30,162
Even reopening
the whole enquiry?

543
00:32:30,237 --> 00:32:31,829
Yes, if the
evidence warrants it.

544
00:32:31,905 --> 00:32:33,202
So, if you'll bear with me

545
00:32:33,273 --> 00:32:35,833
until the full
facts are available,

546
00:32:35,909 --> 00:32:37,240
I'll call another
conference then.

547
00:32:37,311 --> 00:32:39,040
Thank you very much.

548
00:32:42,249 --> 00:32:43,113
Still no Frost?

549
00:32:43,183 --> 00:32:43,911
No, sir.

550
00:32:43,984 --> 00:32:45,042
Well, who's looking for him?

551
00:32:45,118 --> 00:32:46,244
Mr. Toolan.

552
00:32:46,320 --> 00:32:47,048
Well,

553
00:32:47,120 --> 00:32:49,418
several things to make
the day an interesting one.

554
00:32:49,489 --> 00:32:50,922
First, apart from being dead,

555
00:32:50,991 --> 00:32:52,015
he was very healthy.

556
00:32:52,092 --> 00:32:53,184
Suntanned.

557
00:32:53,260 --> 00:32:54,693
Could have
used a health club.

558
00:32:54,761 --> 00:32:56,661
Two, he was gay.

559
00:32:56,730 --> 00:32:58,095
There are certain well,

560
00:32:58,165 --> 00:32:59,792
clear indications.

561
00:32:59,866 --> 00:33:00,696
This could explain

562
00:33:00,767 --> 00:33:03,861
why he used mascara
and faint face make-up.

563
00:33:03,937 --> 00:33:05,905
Might have been
an actor of course.

564
00:33:05,973 --> 00:33:08,237
Three, dental work
wasn't done here.

565
00:33:08,308 --> 00:33:09,502
Maybe America.

566
00:33:09,576 --> 00:33:11,100
It's a long way
to go to the dentist.

567
00:33:11,178 --> 00:33:13,510
Four, he had a severe
fracture of the tibia,

568
00:33:13,580 --> 00:33:14,877
maybe ten years old.

569
00:33:14,948 --> 00:33:16,279
So he took painkillers.

570
00:33:16,350 --> 00:33:18,079
He wasn't a druggie, though.

571
00:33:18,151 --> 00:33:20,984
I'll fill this in and
Diana will give you a copy.

572
00:33:21,054 --> 00:33:24,023
A. Disease or condition
leading directly to death,

573
00:33:24,091 --> 00:33:25,615
Massive constriction
of the throat.

574
00:33:25,692 --> 00:33:27,751
Otherwise
asphyxiation by hanging.

575
00:33:27,828 --> 00:33:29,056
That's definite now, sir?

576
00:33:29,129 --> 00:33:29,993
Yes.

577
00:33:30,063 --> 00:33:32,964
B. Other disease or
condition leading to

578
00:33:33,033 --> 00:33:33,931
A. Drugs overdose,

579
00:33:34,001 --> 00:33:35,195
specifically painkillers

580
00:33:35,268 --> 00:33:37,327
dextroproproxyphene,

581
00:33:37,404 --> 00:33:39,838
which may have produced
unconsciousness.

582
00:33:39,906 --> 00:33:40,736
I see.

583
00:33:40,807 --> 00:33:42,638
C. Have I reported
the case to the coroner

584
00:33:42,709 --> 00:33:43,607
for further action?

585
00:33:43,677 --> 00:33:44,871
Yes, I have.

586
00:33:44,945 --> 00:33:46,105
Which will presumably result

587
00:33:46,179 --> 00:33:48,477
in a verdict of
death by misadventure.

588
00:33:48,548 --> 00:33:50,175
Could it have been murder?

589
00:33:50,250 --> 00:33:51,239
If he was unconscious,

590
00:33:51,318 --> 00:33:52,751
he could hardly
have hanged himself.

591
00:33:52,819 --> 00:33:54,286
Unless he was experimenting.

592
00:33:54,354 --> 00:33:58,313
We'll leave those subtleties
to the coroner, shall we?

593
00:33:58,392 --> 00:34:00,587
Evidence of
identification, your problem.

594
00:34:00,661 --> 00:34:02,822
Diana will give you dental
records and fingerprints

595
00:34:02,896 --> 00:34:05,296
so you can check them with
your usual due diligence.

596
00:34:05,365 --> 00:34:07,094
Found out anything
about him, sergeant?

597
00:34:07,167 --> 00:34:08,691
Not much.

598
00:34:08,769 --> 00:34:09,599
But if it's foul play

599
00:34:09,670 --> 00:34:11,535
it passes to
a senior officer.

600
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:15,524
Oh, Jack.

601
00:34:18,037 --> 00:34:20,267
Well, how are you?

602
00:34:20,340 --> 00:34:22,774
Well, it's very
nice of you to ask,

603
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,369
since I gather you issued
a warrant for my arrest.

604
00:34:26,438 --> 00:34:27,530
Nonsense, Jack,

605
00:34:27,606 --> 00:34:30,166
I just needed you
back here in a hurry.

606
00:34:30,242 --> 00:34:32,301
Why don't you sit down.

607
00:34:32,377 --> 00:34:33,469
All right, thank you.

608
00:34:38,149 --> 00:34:40,777
Now, things are in a real...

609
00:34:40,852 --> 00:34:43,343
You do realize you're still
on the strength don't you?

610
00:34:43,421 --> 00:34:45,616
Didn't you get my
letter of resignation?

611
00:34:45,690 --> 00:34:46,554
Of course.

612
00:34:46,625 --> 00:34:48,525
You handed it to me yourself.

613
00:34:48,593 --> 00:34:50,618
I've kept it here

614
00:34:50,695 --> 00:34:51,787
under lock and key.

615
00:34:54,099 --> 00:34:55,828
Now I realize it was written

616
00:34:55,901 --> 00:35:02,170
in emotional circumstances.

617
00:35:02,240 --> 00:35:03,468
Yes, it was.

618
00:35:03,542 --> 00:35:07,239
I just wanted to give
you time to reconsider.

619
00:35:07,312 --> 00:35:13,308
Well, both of us
time to reconsider.

620
00:35:13,385 --> 00:35:15,216
That's very nice.

621
00:35:15,287 --> 00:35:16,618
And there's me imagining

622
00:35:16,688 --> 00:35:19,350
that you were over the moon.

623
00:35:19,424 --> 00:35:21,085
Jack, I won't deny that

624
00:35:21,159 --> 00:35:23,457
Iife has been quieter
over the last month.

625
00:35:23,528 --> 00:35:25,086
Until lately, anyhow.

626
00:35:25,163 --> 00:35:27,859
But you're missed, Jack.

627
00:35:27,933 --> 00:35:29,457
Sorely missed.

628
00:35:29,534 --> 00:35:30,330
You do realize....

629
00:35:30,402 --> 00:35:33,735
I heard about your
application for promotion.

630
00:35:33,805 --> 00:35:35,033
Really?

631
00:35:35,106 --> 00:35:37,939
Funny how news
gets round, isn't it?

632
00:35:38,009 --> 00:35:40,239
Mind you it
must be a bad time

633
00:35:40,312 --> 00:35:44,339
having a senior
officer retire.

634
00:35:44,416 --> 00:35:46,941
Especially the
Chief Constable's darling.

635
00:35:47,018 --> 00:35:48,144
That has got
nothing to do with it.

636
00:35:48,219 --> 00:35:51,279
Private ambition doesn't
come into this at all.

637
00:35:51,356 --> 00:35:52,584
The point is
that since you left

638
00:35:52,657 --> 00:35:54,818
we've had two major
problems at this station,

639
00:35:54,893 --> 00:35:56,724
both of them
connected with you.

640
00:35:56,795 --> 00:35:58,490
First it was
the time sheets...

641
00:35:58,563 --> 00:35:59,825
You haven't called
me back here

642
00:35:59,898 --> 00:36:01,525
to talk about time
sheets, have you?

643
00:36:01,600 --> 00:36:04,899
These days we need to
keep a very tight ship.

644
00:36:04,970 --> 00:36:07,268
Now it's the
Black Farm Murder.

645
00:36:07,339 --> 00:36:09,068
But you've seen
the press reports.

646
00:36:09,140 --> 00:36:12,132
It seems we can't
settle it without you.

647
00:36:12,210 --> 00:36:14,678
It seems to be a
very poor reflection

648
00:36:14,746 --> 00:36:15,974
on the other
officers, doesn't it?

649
00:36:16,047 --> 00:36:18,948
Because when we looked
for the file it wasn't there.

650
00:36:19,017 --> 00:36:19,949
And even if it had been

651
00:36:20,018 --> 00:36:21,542
I don't suppose there'd
have been anything
in it, would there?

652
00:36:21,620 --> 00:36:22,917
Now I want you to
get back to that case,

653
00:36:22,988 --> 00:36:25,320
and this time I want
you to do things properly.

654
00:36:25,390 --> 00:36:26,857
Everything in the notebook,

655
00:36:26,925 --> 00:36:28,688
everything on
the record sheet.

656
00:36:28,760 --> 00:36:30,159
Expenses properly kept,

657
00:36:30,228 --> 00:36:31,786
files stored on the computer.

658
00:36:31,863 --> 00:36:33,956
Every problem I have in
this station at the moment

659
00:36:34,032 --> 00:36:35,932
is down to you and
your slipshod ways.

660
00:36:36,001 --> 00:36:39,095
Just remember,
nobody's indispensable.

661
00:36:43,341 --> 00:36:46,708
Well, all right then you
probably are indispensable!

662
00:36:51,983 --> 00:36:53,712
Jack.

663
00:36:57,188 --> 00:36:59,213
I'm going to
tear this letter up.

664
00:36:59,290 --> 00:37:01,884
No, I think I'd better
hold onto it, sir.

665
00:37:01,960 --> 00:37:02,790
You never know.

666
00:37:02,861 --> 00:37:05,887
One of us might
want to reconsider.

667
00:37:05,964 --> 00:37:08,933
Anyway, good luck sir.

668
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:10,490
What?

669
00:37:10,568 --> 00:37:11,535
With your promotion.

670
00:37:11,603 --> 00:37:12,865
You know,

671
00:37:12,937 --> 00:37:14,734
onward and upward.

672
00:37:18,910 --> 00:37:19,604
Good morning.

673
00:37:19,678 --> 00:37:20,440
Nice to see you, guv.

674
00:37:20,512 --> 00:37:21,274
Thank you.

675
00:37:21,346 --> 00:37:21,971
Jack?
Yes?

676
00:37:22,047 --> 00:37:24,743
Oh come on tell
me, how was it?

677
00:37:24,816 --> 00:37:26,977
Oh, you know, as well
as can be expected.

678
00:37:27,052 --> 00:37:29,486
He said I could
either be a DI again,

679
00:37:29,554 --> 00:37:30,612
or go to prison.

680
00:37:30,689 --> 00:37:32,316
Oh, difficult choice, eh?

681
00:37:32,390 --> 00:37:34,654
Yeah, you could...

682
00:37:34,726 --> 00:37:37,661
Well, what the
hell is going on here?

683
00:37:37,729 --> 00:37:39,492
You turn your
back for five minutes

684
00:37:39,564 --> 00:37:40,826
and look what happens.

685
00:37:40,899 --> 00:37:42,389
You're lucky your
stuff's here at all.

686
00:37:42,467 --> 00:37:44,162
Mullett said put
it in the corridor.

687
00:37:44,235 --> 00:37:45,395
Yeah, but who did this?

688
00:37:45,470 --> 00:37:47,631
Look they've completely
ruined my filing system.

689
00:37:47,706 --> 00:37:50,334
Sorry, guv, it was me.

690
00:37:50,408 --> 00:37:51,841
Well, well.

691
00:37:51,910 --> 00:37:54,105
WPC Hazel Wallace!

692
00:37:54,179 --> 00:37:56,010
What are you doing here
without your clothes on?

693
00:37:56,081 --> 00:37:57,571
I've been made up.

694
00:37:57,649 --> 00:37:58,581
Detective Sergeant.

695
00:37:58,650 --> 00:37:59,981
Really, good, well done.

696
00:38:00,051 --> 00:38:02,281
If I'd known that I'd
have been back weeks ago.

697
00:38:02,353 --> 00:38:05,083
Well, you were one reason
I asked for some time here.

698
00:38:05,156 --> 00:38:06,145
Oh, really.

699
00:38:06,224 --> 00:38:07,919
George, the
Riverside Apartments case.

700
00:38:07,992 --> 00:38:09,550
Looks like it
might not be suicide.

701
00:38:09,627 --> 00:38:11,151
Well, shouldn't I be
told about it then?

702
00:38:11,229 --> 00:38:12,594
(Phone ringing)

703
00:38:12,664 --> 00:38:14,894
Frost.

704
00:38:14,966 --> 00:38:16,957
Yes, yes, yes it is.

705
00:38:17,035 --> 00:38:18,229
Yes, all right.

706
00:38:18,303 --> 00:38:20,464
Yes, she is.

707
00:38:20,538 --> 00:38:23,063
All right, thank you Ernie.

708
00:38:23,141 --> 00:38:24,733
That was Ernie Trigg.

709
00:38:24,809 --> 00:38:27,209
He's got something
for you downstairs,

710
00:38:27,278 --> 00:38:28,336
and he says...

711
00:38:28,413 --> 00:38:30,278
You're never
going to believe this.

712
00:38:30,348 --> 00:38:31,440
I've never seen anything...

713
00:38:31,516 --> 00:38:33,541
All right, Ernie,
just try us will you?

714
00:38:33,618 --> 00:38:34,277
All right.

715
00:38:34,352 --> 00:38:36,081
Now, this death at
Riverside Apartments.

716
00:38:36,154 --> 00:38:38,588
It's just been confirmed
as a possible suspicious.

717
00:38:38,656 --> 00:38:39,918
Oh, right.

718
00:38:39,991 --> 00:38:41,288
Well, these are
the fingerprints

719
00:38:41,359 --> 00:38:43,190
taken at the crime
scene by the SOCOS.

720
00:38:43,261 --> 00:38:44,592
Most are the victim's.

721
00:38:44,662 --> 00:38:46,926
A man we think is
called Lester Bryce-Jones.

722
00:38:46,998 --> 00:38:49,023
Yeah, all right,
get the lights, will you?

723
00:38:49,100 --> 00:38:51,694
But this one, FP1 7,

724
00:38:51,770 --> 00:38:53,260
that's an unident.

725
00:38:53,338 --> 00:38:54,669
Except, see,

726
00:38:54,739 --> 00:38:56,331
we've got a match.

727
00:38:56,407 --> 00:38:59,501
Prints from our own files.

728
00:38:59,577 --> 00:39:01,477
Identical, right?

729
00:39:01,546 --> 00:39:04,515
Yes, well, that's what
it looks like Ernie.

730
00:39:04,582 --> 00:39:05,947
Whose are these?

731
00:39:06,017 --> 00:39:07,917
Well, that's what you're
not going to believe.

732
00:39:07,986 --> 00:39:10,978
Those prints are from an
old case of yours, Jack.

733
00:39:11,055 --> 00:39:12,716
The Appendix Man?

734
00:39:12,791 --> 00:39:14,656
Remember?

735
00:39:16,561 --> 00:39:19,291
The Appendix Man?

736
00:39:19,364 --> 00:39:21,491
Oh, don't be daft.

737
00:39:21,566 --> 00:39:24,262
The Appendix Man
died a year ago.

738
00:39:24,335 --> 00:39:25,632
He was fished
out of the river.

739
00:39:25,703 --> 00:39:27,227
He was drowned,
I know 'cos I was there.

740
00:39:27,305 --> 00:39:28,101
So was I Guv,

741
00:39:28,173 --> 00:39:29,140
Yeah.

742
00:39:29,207 --> 00:39:30,902
And then because we
couldn't identify him

743
00:39:30,975 --> 00:39:33,136
he was stuffed into the
morgue for ten months.

744
00:39:33,211 --> 00:39:35,145
They don't do that
without good reason.

745
00:39:35,213 --> 00:39:36,510
I know that, Jack.

746
00:39:36,581 --> 00:39:40,779
Come on, this is ridiculous.

747
00:39:40,852 --> 00:39:41,876
Are you trying to tell me

748
00:39:41,953 --> 00:39:44,046
that a bloke who
died a year ago

749
00:39:44,122 --> 00:39:45,919
hops out of his coffin,

750
00:39:45,990 --> 00:39:48,515
hitches a lift down to
Riverside Apartments,

751
00:39:48,593 --> 00:39:49,617
commits a murder,

752
00:39:49,694 --> 00:39:51,355
then nips back
to the graveyard

753
00:39:51,429 --> 00:39:54,398
probably stopping off at
the Red Lion for a pint?

754
00:39:54,465 --> 00:39:55,898
Well, there it is Jack.

755
00:39:55,967 --> 00:39:58,993
Scientific fact.

756
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:02,059
He's called
Lester Bryce-Jones,

757
00:40:02,136 --> 00:40:02,966
we think.

758
00:40:03,037 --> 00:40:05,335
But we've
still not established
evidence of identity.

759
00:40:05,406 --> 00:40:07,306
Check banks,
social security,

760
00:40:07,375 --> 00:40:08,672
especially hospitals.

761
00:40:08,743 --> 00:40:11,940
Another thing, check
gay clubs and gyms,

762
00:40:12,012 --> 00:40:13,309
he was into exercise.

763
00:40:13,381 --> 00:40:15,941
In more ways
than one, apparently.

764
00:40:16,016 --> 00:40:18,484
(Applause)

765
00:40:18,552 --> 00:40:19,450
Yes, all right, thank you.

766
00:40:19,520 --> 00:40:22,148
Yes, I'm back,
but it's not all good news.

767
00:40:22,223 --> 00:40:25,249
Hornrim Harry is still here.

768
00:40:25,326 --> 00:40:27,760
All right, come on,
let's pay attention.

769
00:40:27,828 --> 00:40:30,695
It appears that
we've got two unidents.

770
00:40:30,765 --> 00:40:32,426
One old one and one new one.

771
00:40:32,500 --> 00:40:35,060
Now, can anyone tell
me do they remember him?

772
00:40:35,136 --> 00:40:36,569
We all do, guv.

773
00:40:36,637 --> 00:40:38,298
Yes, but you
didn't though, did you?

774
00:40:38,372 --> 00:40:39,896
That's The
Appendix Man, right?

775
00:40:39,974 --> 00:40:40,963
Yes, well done, Jordan.

776
00:40:41,041 --> 00:40:42,099
The Appendix Man.

777
00:40:42,176 --> 00:40:45,236
So called because one
Saturday last summer,

778
00:40:45,312 --> 00:40:46,870
when Denton Football club

779
00:40:46,947 --> 00:40:48,972
was playing it's
big match at home,

780
00:40:49,049 --> 00:40:52,746
he walked out of Denton
General in a hospital gown

781
00:40:52,820 --> 00:40:57,120
even though his appendix
was about to burst.

782
00:40:57,191 --> 00:40:58,886
A few hours later

783
00:40:58,959 --> 00:41:02,451
he was fished out
of the river DED.

784
00:41:02,530 --> 00:41:04,498
We thought he
might be a head case.

785
00:41:04,565 --> 00:41:06,760
Yeah, well, we
checked out everything.

786
00:41:06,834 --> 00:41:09,462
Hospital records,
dentistry, fingerprints.

787
00:41:09,537 --> 00:41:11,869
They all came back zero.

788
00:41:11,939 --> 00:41:14,066
Now, is that his
stuff down there?

789
00:41:14,141 --> 00:41:14,903
Yes.

790
00:41:14,975 --> 00:41:17,375
So, we had a
man without a past,

791
00:41:17,445 --> 00:41:20,312
without a present
and without a future.

792
00:41:20,381 --> 00:41:22,212
Everything that
we know about him

793
00:41:22,283 --> 00:41:24,251
is here on this table.

794
00:41:24,318 --> 00:41:26,616
Right, so, come and
take a look everybody.

795
00:41:26,687 --> 00:41:28,814
Especially the newcomers.

796
00:41:30,624 --> 00:41:31,784
Right.

797
00:41:31,859 --> 00:41:33,224
What have we got.

798
00:41:33,294 --> 00:41:34,261
Hospital gown.

799
00:41:34,328 --> 00:41:37,229
Hospital bracelet
with a number on it,

800
00:41:37,298 --> 00:41:38,094
and his clothes.

801
00:41:38,165 --> 00:41:39,757
All good quality but worn.

802
00:41:39,834 --> 00:41:41,096
Might have been
down on his luck.

803
00:41:41,168 --> 00:41:42,192
Yeah, well, could be.

804
00:41:42,269 --> 00:41:43,327
There was the
driving licence, guv.

805
00:41:43,404 --> 00:41:45,770
Oh yes, and the
driving licence.

806
00:41:45,840 --> 00:41:49,241
Now this driving licence was
found in his jacket pocket

807
00:41:49,310 --> 00:41:51,835
and it's in the name
of Colin Drysdale.

808
00:41:51,912 --> 00:41:55,609
But Colin Drysdale
is a local headmaster

809
00:41:55,683 --> 00:42:00,484
who somehow allowed it
to be nicked by a tom.

810
00:42:00,554 --> 00:42:01,680
All right.

811
00:42:01,755 --> 00:42:02,813
So, there you have it.

812
00:42:02,890 --> 00:42:05,324
The Appendix Man.

813
00:42:05,392 --> 00:42:06,154
Sorry, sir.

814
00:42:06,227 --> 00:42:07,990
Yes.

