00:53:20,467 --> 00:53:21,695
But these don't, do they?

1084
00:53:21,768 --> 00:53:22,666
No, guv.

1085
00:53:22,736 --> 00:53:24,465
No.

1086
00:53:24,538 --> 00:53:25,505
Do you know what I think?

1087
00:53:25,572 --> 00:53:27,506
I think if you can't find
any of his paperwork,

1088
00:53:27,574 --> 00:53:28,541
or his passport,

1089
00:53:28,608 --> 00:53:29,597
anything like that,

1090
00:53:29,676 --> 00:53:30,904
that may mean

1091
00:53:30,977 --> 00:53:33,878
that he's got a place
somewhere else, you know.

1092
00:54:14,554 --> 00:54:15,919
It's all right,
dear, it's all right.

1093
00:54:15,989 --> 00:54:17,752
It's all been cleared up.

1094
00:54:17,824 --> 00:54:20,019
Okay.

1095
00:54:20,093 --> 00:54:23,585
Now then, you
came in with the key.

1096
00:54:23,663 --> 00:54:24,960
So what did you see?

1097
00:54:25,031 --> 00:54:25,929
Just take me through it.

1098
00:54:25,999 --> 00:54:27,864
You were looking
for the cat, yes?

1099
00:54:27,934 --> 00:54:28,832
Yes.

1100
00:54:28,902 --> 00:54:29,960
Actually I liked
it when he's away.

1101
00:54:30,036 --> 00:54:32,527
Feeding the cat gave
me something to do.

1102
00:54:32,606 --> 00:54:33,436
Just tell me,

1103
00:54:33,506 --> 00:54:34,996
what did you see

1104
00:54:35,075 --> 00:54:39,205
before you found poor
Mr. Bryce-Jones?

1105
00:54:39,279 --> 00:54:42,146
I saw pills on the table.

1106
00:54:42,215 --> 00:54:43,910
Some on the floor.

1107
00:54:43,984 --> 00:54:47,852
Then the cat was
yowling and then I saw...

1108
00:54:47,921 --> 00:54:50,321
Yes, yes, of course.

1109
00:54:50,390 --> 00:54:52,449
Just think back Leonie.

1110
00:54:52,525 --> 00:54:54,789
When you first came in.

1111
00:54:54,861 --> 00:54:56,260
Was anything missing?

1112
00:54:56,329 --> 00:54:59,196
The picture, you mean.

1113
00:54:59,266 --> 00:55:01,393
Yes, most probably.

1114
00:55:01,468 --> 00:55:04,130
So, go on.

1115
00:55:04,204 --> 00:55:06,536
When I came home from
school the door was open.

1116
00:55:06,606 --> 00:55:08,801
There was a painting
on the easel there.

1117
00:55:08,875 --> 00:55:10,843
Then when I came for
Shangri it had gone.

1118
00:55:10,910 --> 00:55:14,971
(Phone ringing)

1119
00:55:15,048 --> 00:55:17,175
Do you know much
about painting, Leonie?

1120
00:55:17,250 --> 00:55:17,978
Not a lot.

1121
00:55:18,051 --> 00:55:20,042
But I think it was a Hockney.

1122
00:55:20,120 --> 00:55:21,917
A Hockney?

1123
00:55:21,988 --> 00:55:23,512
Are you sure?

1124
00:55:23,590 --> 00:55:24,784
Well, it had to be, didn't it?

1125
00:55:24,858 --> 00:55:26,155
It had a swimming pool in it.

1126
00:55:26,226 --> 00:55:27,056
Right, thanks.

1127
00:55:27,127 --> 00:55:28,651
Just stay where you are,
we'll be right over.

1128
00:55:28,728 --> 00:55:29,456
Guv.

1129
00:55:29,529 --> 00:55:30,928
That address
in Infirmary Road.

1130
00:55:30,997 --> 00:55:31,964
Someone's been using it.

1131
00:55:32,032 --> 00:55:34,364
A man in a hospital coat.

1132
00:55:34,434 --> 00:55:35,765
Really?

1133
00:55:35,835 --> 00:55:36,426
Thank you.

1134
00:55:36,503 --> 00:55:38,403
Thank you very much, Leonie.

1135
00:55:40,540 --> 00:55:43,236
The neighbors say
he comes quite often.

1136
00:55:43,310 --> 00:55:44,902
You know, picks
up mail and stuff.

1137
00:55:44,978 --> 00:55:46,002
All right.

1138
00:55:49,549 --> 00:55:51,346
Aha.

1139
00:56:00,994 --> 00:56:01,824
Look at this, guv.

1140
00:56:01,895 --> 00:56:02,759
What?

1141
00:56:02,829 --> 00:56:04,854
Addressed to
Mr. Leslie Jackson.

1142
00:56:04,931 --> 00:56:06,023
Right.

1143
00:56:06,099 --> 00:56:07,031
Call for backup.

1144
00:56:07,100 --> 00:56:09,034
I want this whole
place searched.

1145
00:56:09,102 --> 00:56:11,002
Alpha bravo 16 to Control?

1146
00:56:32,726 --> 00:56:34,353
Hazel!

1147
00:56:37,964 --> 00:56:40,159
Oh, thank you.

1148
00:56:40,233 --> 00:56:41,700
Mr. Frost,

1149
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:43,025
you might have said.

1150
00:56:43,102 --> 00:56:44,763
You're not one, are you?

1151
00:56:47,273 --> 00:56:49,332
Not one what?

1152
00:56:49,408 --> 00:56:50,932
Not a policeman.

1153
00:56:51,010 --> 00:56:52,409
The barman at the
Cave Club told me...

1154
00:56:52,478 --> 00:56:54,946
Yes, only in the afternoons.

1155
00:56:55,014 --> 00:56:57,676
And you shouldn't listen
to gossip, should you.

1156
00:56:57,750 --> 00:56:59,615
And you always seemed so nice.

1157
00:56:59,685 --> 00:57:00,913
Yeah, well.

1158
00:57:03,022 --> 00:57:05,786
Yeah, talking
about that Cave Club.

1159
00:57:05,858 --> 00:57:08,122
Is it a good place
to meet people, is it?

1160
00:57:08,194 --> 00:57:09,388
I should hope so,

1161
00:57:09,462 --> 00:57:11,089
that's what it's for.

1162
00:57:14,333 --> 00:57:16,096
Did you ever see him there?

1163
00:57:19,205 --> 00:57:20,433
No.

1164
00:57:20,506 --> 00:57:22,497
I've never seen
him before in my life.

1165
00:57:22,575 --> 00:57:24,668
Is he a friend of yours?

1166
00:57:24,744 --> 00:57:25,836
No not really.

1167
00:57:25,911 --> 00:57:27,811
I never knew him
when he was alive.

1168
00:57:27,880 --> 00:57:30,576
Now no-one seems to know
him now that he's dead.

1169
00:57:30,650 --> 00:57:34,177
Oh dear, is he?

1170
00:57:34,253 --> 00:57:37,552
Found drowned in a
river about a year ago.

1171
00:57:40,760 --> 00:57:41,624
What about this one?

1172
00:57:41,694 --> 00:57:43,389
Have you ever seen him there?

1173
00:57:43,462 --> 00:57:45,828
His name's Leslie Jackson.

1174
00:57:45,898 --> 00:57:47,593
Now him I'm not sure.

1175
00:57:47,667 --> 00:57:50,397
I think I just might have.

1176
00:57:50,469 --> 00:57:52,630
I'll go and ask
Donald, all right?

1177
00:57:52,705 --> 00:57:54,798
Yes, please do, Brian.

1178
00:58:00,913 --> 00:58:02,380
Yes?

1179
00:58:08,954 --> 00:58:10,046
Sorry, Mr. Frost.

1180
00:58:10,122 --> 00:58:12,716
Donald says nice
man but definitely no.

1181
00:58:12,792 --> 00:58:13,486
Oh, right.

1182
00:58:13,559 --> 00:58:15,049
Thank you for trying Brian.

1183
00:58:15,127 --> 00:58:16,287
Could I have
another pot of tea?

1184
00:58:16,362 --> 00:58:18,523
Of course you can, Inspector.

1185
00:58:30,743 --> 00:58:32,040
Morning, Jack.

1186
00:58:32,111 --> 00:58:33,908
Morning Harry.

1187
00:58:33,979 --> 00:58:36,504
I've had ten quid's worth
on pump number three.

1188
00:58:36,582 --> 00:58:37,446
There you go.

1189
00:58:37,516 --> 00:58:38,380
Do you want a
receipt for that?

1190
00:58:38,451 --> 00:58:39,440
Yes please.

1191
00:58:39,518 --> 00:58:40,985
And I want one of these,

1192
00:58:41,053 --> 00:58:42,350
a Chicken Duchesse

1193
00:58:42,421 --> 00:58:45,913
with a light curry
sauce on wholemeal.

1194
00:58:45,991 --> 00:58:48,118
That's expired, I see.

1195
00:58:51,630 --> 00:58:53,120
Here, you couldn't
let me have twenty or so

1196
00:58:53,199 --> 00:58:55,326
of those blank
receipts could you?

1197
00:58:55,401 --> 00:58:58,461
You'd be helping me out
with a very important case.

1198
00:58:58,537 --> 00:59:00,004
Yeah, course I can Jack.

1199
00:59:00,072 --> 00:59:00,868
You're a good man.

1200
00:59:00,940 --> 00:59:02,271
And the sarnie's on the house.

1201
00:59:02,341 --> 00:59:03,774
Oh, cheers.

1202
00:59:12,017 --> 00:59:13,644
I've seen his Bank Manager.

1203
00:59:13,719 --> 00:59:15,277
Guess how much in his account?

1204
00:59:15,354 --> 00:59:18,551
Twenty five thousand.

1205
00:59:18,624 --> 00:59:20,819
Maybe I should be
a hospital porter.

1206
00:59:20,893 --> 00:59:21,860
Maybe.

1207
00:59:23,195 --> 00:59:25,186
Anything from
St. Martin's School of Art?

1208
00:59:25,264 --> 00:59:25,992
Yes.

1209
00:59:26,065 --> 00:59:27,965
He was known as
Lionel Jacobs there.

1210
00:59:28,033 --> 00:59:30,263
Enrolled autumn 1993,

1211
00:59:30,336 --> 00:59:32,099
and then quit after Christmas.

1212
00:59:32,171 --> 00:59:33,229
He took a course in...

1213
00:59:33,305 --> 00:59:34,738
Basket-weaving?

1214
00:59:34,807 --> 00:59:35,865
Not at all.

1215
00:59:35,941 --> 00:59:37,101
Figure drawing.

1216
00:59:37,176 --> 00:59:38,200
Did quite well.

1217
00:59:38,277 --> 00:59:41,508
He said he came from
Brisbane in Australia.

1218
00:59:41,580 --> 00:59:43,013
So that's Perth, now Brisbane.

1219
00:59:43,082 --> 00:59:44,572
I bet he came from Sydney.

1220
00:59:44,650 --> 00:59:45,742
Unless it was Melbourne.

1221
00:59:45,818 --> 00:59:47,547
What about Adelaide?

1222
00:59:47,620 --> 00:59:48,609
Anyone seen Jack Frost?

1223
00:59:48,687 --> 00:59:49,779
No.

1224
00:59:49,855 --> 00:59:51,379
Only Mr. Mullett's
getting a bit rattled.

1225
00:59:51,457 --> 00:59:52,788
He wants things
tidying up quick.

1226
00:59:52,858 --> 00:59:53,688
What's the news?

1227
00:59:53,759 --> 00:59:55,192
Well, he's got another
interview on Wednesday.

1228
00:59:55,261 --> 00:59:56,785
So, fingers crossed.

1229
00:59:56,862 --> 00:59:58,557
Ok, thanks very much.

1230
00:59:58,631 --> 00:59:59,723
Art squad.

1231
00:59:59,799 --> 01:00:01,164
They need a
detailed description

1232
01:00:01,233 --> 01:00:02,632
on those paintings.

1233
01:00:02,701 --> 01:00:05,192
But they do say
there was a Hockney

1234
01:00:05,271 --> 01:00:07,705
among the pictures
stolen from Black Farm.

1235
01:00:07,773 --> 01:00:10,571
Pity Jack's lost
the file, isn't it?

1236
01:00:17,917 --> 01:00:20,784
Yeah, that's nice.

1237
01:00:20,853 --> 01:00:23,185
I feel better already.

1238
01:00:23,255 --> 01:00:25,223
That's because I'm
giving you deep healing

1239
01:00:25,291 --> 01:00:27,384
along with the massage.

1240
01:00:30,296 --> 01:00:32,457
Got many clients, have you?

1241
01:00:32,531 --> 01:00:35,989
A lot of corporate ones, yes.

1242
01:00:36,068 --> 01:00:39,560
I've heard it
changes people's lives.

1243
01:00:39,638 --> 01:00:43,699
We've helped a lot of
people discover themselves.

1244
01:00:49,248 --> 01:00:52,979
Trouble with me is
I'm always so busy.

1245
01:00:57,890 --> 01:01:00,017
There.

1246
01:01:00,092 --> 01:01:01,650
Well, if you
can't find a window,

1247
01:01:01,727 --> 01:01:03,319
I can always give you
a twenty minute massage

1248
01:01:03,395 --> 01:01:04,828
at your desk.

1249
01:01:04,897 --> 01:01:08,264
Assuming you've
got a quiet desk.

1250
01:01:08,334 --> 01:01:10,859
Would you like me to
take your business number?

1251
01:01:10,936 --> 01:01:12,130
Yes.

1252
01:01:12,204 --> 01:01:13,171
Yeah, I would.

1253
01:01:13,239 --> 01:01:15,298
That's a very good idea.

1254
01:01:15,374 --> 01:01:16,864
There it is.

1255
01:01:16,942 --> 01:01:17,738
Oh no.

1256
01:01:17,810 --> 01:01:20,108
Not here too.

1257
01:01:20,179 --> 01:01:21,203
Morning, Gaynor.

1258
01:01:21,280 --> 01:01:22,542
Just go through and undress,

1259
01:01:22,615 --> 01:01:25,277
I'll be with you in a minute.

1260
01:01:25,351 --> 01:01:28,184
I am busy, as you can see.

1261
01:01:28,254 --> 01:01:31,121
Yes, nice work
if you can get it.

1262
01:01:31,190 --> 01:01:33,522
I assume this is about
the man across the hall?

1263
01:01:33,592 --> 01:01:34,991
Lester Bryce-Jones.

1264
01:01:35,060 --> 01:01:36,960
Yes, if that
was his real name.

1265
01:01:37,029 --> 01:01:40,556
He seems to be using
quite a lot of names recently.

1266
01:01:40,633 --> 01:01:41,565
Did he?

1267
01:01:41,634 --> 01:01:42,464
I wouldn't know.

1268
01:01:42,534 --> 01:01:44,525
I knew very little about him.

1269
01:01:44,603 --> 01:01:48,664
That'll be fifteen
pounds please.

1270
01:01:48,741 --> 01:01:49,503
Yes.

1271
01:01:49,575 --> 01:01:50,633
All right.

1272
01:01:52,711 --> 01:01:55,475
Your daughter, Leonie
has been very helpful.

1273
01:01:55,547 --> 01:01:56,775
Yes I know.

1274
01:01:56,849 --> 01:01:59,044
She's also very upset.

1275
01:01:59,118 --> 01:02:01,018
Isn't it time
you left her alone?

1276
01:02:01,086 --> 01:02:03,054
She's a very clever girl.

1277
01:02:03,122 --> 01:02:05,420
Does she know a
lot about modern art?

1278
01:02:05,491 --> 01:02:06,480
About art?

1279
01:02:06,558 --> 01:02:09,425
Not much, she's only fifteen.

1280
01:02:09,495 --> 01:02:11,053
So you would say
that she wouldn't know

1281
01:02:11,130 --> 01:02:14,429
the difference between
a hockeystick and a Hockney?

1282
01:02:14,500 --> 01:02:17,162
A Hockney?

1283
01:02:17,236 --> 01:02:19,136
She reckons that she
saw a Hockney painting

1284
01:02:19,204 --> 01:02:21,468
in Lester Bryce's
flat that afternoon.

1285
01:02:21,540 --> 01:02:24,873
Did she?

1286
01:02:24,944 --> 01:02:27,538
Only it isn't there now.

1287
01:02:27,613 --> 01:02:29,342
Yes, well, I'd say
that's about as likely

1288
01:02:29,415 --> 01:02:30,746
as seeing the
Royal Yacht Britannia

1289
01:02:30,816 --> 01:02:32,681
in the Denton River,
wouldn't you?

1290
01:02:32,751 --> 01:02:34,241
Leonie is smart,

1291
01:02:34,320 --> 01:02:36,447
but I wouldn't trust
her with your investments.

1292
01:02:36,522 --> 01:02:39,218
Now, can you see
your own way out?

1293
01:03:02,414 --> 01:03:03,108
Ah, Frost.

1294
01:03:03,182 --> 01:03:03,876
Ah, sir.

1295
01:03:03,949 --> 01:03:05,610
Very glad to hear you've
got another interview.

1296
01:03:05,684 --> 01:03:07,413
I want you in my
office immediately.

1297
01:03:07,486 --> 01:03:08,248
I'm just on my way...

1298
01:03:08,320 --> 01:03:09,446
Whatever it is, it can wait.

1299
01:03:09,521 --> 01:03:10,510
The Black Farm murder can't.

1300
01:03:10,589 --> 01:03:11,681
I've got the
press all over me.

1301
01:03:11,757 --> 01:03:12,781
Now, have you found that file?

1302
01:03:12,858 --> 01:03:13,984
I'm still looking for it.

1303
01:03:14,059 --> 01:03:14,923
And I want your time sheets.

1304
01:03:14,994 --> 01:03:16,052
And your petrol expenses.

1305
01:03:16,128 --> 01:03:17,186
And your report on
the Riverside Murder.

1306
01:03:17,262 --> 01:03:19,287
And what's all this
about The Appendix Man?

1307
01:03:19,365 --> 01:03:20,229
Good morning, sir.

1308
01:03:20,299 --> 01:03:21,266
Good morning.

1309
01:03:21,333 --> 01:03:22,197
Just bringing your coffee.

1310
01:03:22,267 --> 01:03:23,029
Yes, sir.

1311
01:03:23,102 --> 01:03:23,932
Shall I take it upstairs?

1312
01:03:24,003 --> 01:03:25,834
Yes, please do yes,
thank you Sergeant Brady.

1313
01:03:25,904 --> 01:03:27,337
Well?

1314
01:03:30,376 --> 01:03:31,274
I tell you Jack,

1315
01:03:31,343 --> 01:03:33,004
no way those prints are wrong.

1316
01:03:33,078 --> 01:03:36,104
Crossed checked
in the old faithful.

1317
01:03:36,181 --> 01:03:38,240
Yes, but, hang on.

1318
01:03:38,317 --> 01:03:41,377
Not all of those prints
are ours, are they?

1319
01:03:41,453 --> 01:03:46,447
The Appendix Man's came
from the Pathology lab.

1320
01:03:46,525 --> 01:03:47,890
Because that's
where they took him

1321
01:03:47,960 --> 01:03:49,951
when he came out of the river.

1322
01:03:50,029 --> 01:03:51,428
You know Jack,
it would help a lot

1323
01:03:51,497 --> 01:03:52,964
if you didn't
lose all your files.

1324
01:03:53,032 --> 01:03:54,693
Yeah.

1325
01:03:54,767 --> 01:03:56,894
I don't know though.

1326
01:03:56,969 --> 01:03:58,698
Here, have a sandwich.

1327
01:03:58,771 --> 01:04:00,534
Thanks for the tea.

1328
01:04:12,351 --> 01:04:13,147
Morning, doc.

1329
01:04:13,218 --> 01:04:14,344
Remember me?

1330
01:04:14,420 --> 01:04:16,012
All too well.

1331
01:04:16,088 --> 01:04:18,989
I thought you'd
retired from the force.

1332
01:04:19,058 --> 01:04:20,923
Suddenly life seemed
far more pleasant.

1333
01:04:20,993 --> 01:04:23,860
Oh, just for once
this isn't one of yours.

1334
01:04:23,929 --> 01:04:24,588
Really?

1335
01:04:24,663 --> 01:04:26,426
Who are you doing
it for, a friend?

1336
01:04:26,498 --> 01:04:27,487
Knife?

1337
01:04:30,769 --> 01:04:31,701
What is it, Inspector?

1338
01:04:31,770 --> 01:04:35,103
Ah, do you remember
the Appendix Man?

1339
01:04:35,174 --> 01:04:37,074
How could I ever forget him?

1340
01:04:37,142 --> 01:04:38,666
Never identified him, did you?

1341
01:04:38,744 --> 01:04:41,008
Which is why he slept
in the morgue for so long.

1342
01:04:41,080 --> 01:04:42,308
Well, he's not
there now, is he?

1343
01:04:42,381 --> 01:04:43,370
No, he's not there now.

1344
01:04:43,449 --> 01:04:44,939
He went to an unmarked grave.

1345
01:04:45,017 --> 01:04:46,678
You signed the
request to the coroner.

1346
01:04:46,752 --> 01:04:47,650
Yes, I know.

1347
01:04:47,719 --> 01:04:49,653
And now I've got
to dig him up.

1348
01:04:49,721 --> 01:04:50,745
I beg your pardon?

1349
01:04:50,823 --> 01:04:52,620
We're reopening the case.

1350
01:04:52,691 --> 01:04:54,352
There never was a case.

1351
01:04:54,426 --> 01:04:56,155
The man had every
right to leave hospital

1352
01:04:56,228 --> 01:04:57,320
if he wanted to,

1353
01:04:57,396 --> 01:04:59,193
however foolish
he might have been.

1354
01:04:59,264 --> 01:05:00,390
As for his death,

1355
01:05:00,466 --> 01:05:02,024
he drowned
himself, didn't he?

1356
01:05:02,101 --> 01:05:04,194
I would if I was
in that kind of pain.

1357
01:05:04,269 --> 01:05:06,396
The truth is doc,

1358
01:05:06,472 --> 01:05:09,100
it's all rather embarrassing.

1359
01:05:09,174 --> 01:05:10,163
But they've gone

1360
01:05:10,242 --> 01:05:15,373
and lost your original
pathology report.

1361
01:05:15,447 --> 01:05:17,244
So I thought
I'd just pop in here

1362
01:05:17,316 --> 01:05:20,843
and see if you've got
a copy in your files.

1363
01:05:20,919 --> 01:05:21,886
Diana.

1364
01:05:21,954 --> 01:05:25,117
Will you see what you can
do for this impossible man?

1365
01:05:25,190 --> 01:05:26,452
Thank you.

1366
01:05:33,098 --> 01:05:34,497
DC Jordan?

1367
01:05:34,566 --> 01:05:37,467
Joanna Kenwothy
at Ansty Galleries.

1368
01:05:37,536 --> 01:05:39,902
I thought you might
be interested.

1369
01:05:39,972 --> 01:05:41,633
Someone's just
offered us a painting

1370
01:05:41,707 --> 01:05:45,268
we feel very doubtful about.

1371
01:05:45,344 --> 01:05:48,040
No a woman.

1372
01:05:48,113 --> 01:05:49,341
We're awfully
busy at the moment,

1373
01:05:49,414 --> 01:05:52,315
but if you wanted
to stop by sometime.

1374
01:05:56,188 --> 01:05:57,485
There.

1375
01:05:57,556 --> 01:05:58,648
Everything you need?

1376
01:05:58,724 --> 01:05:59,520
All right.

1377
01:05:59,591 --> 01:06:01,582
Thank you.

1378
01:06:01,660 --> 01:06:04,322
There is just one thing.

1379
01:06:04,396 --> 01:06:07,297
Could you explain to
me exactly what you do

1380
01:06:07,366 --> 01:06:09,561
when you perform
a post mortem.

1381
01:06:09,635 --> 01:06:11,694
I'm sure Dr. Simpkins would
be delighted to show you.

1382
01:06:11,770 --> 01:06:12,759
Do come through.

1383
01:06:12,838 --> 01:06:14,362
No no, sorry
I didn't mean that.

1384
01:06:14,439 --> 01:06:17,840
I meant how do you actually
make out the report?

1385
01:06:17,910 --> 01:06:19,400
It's perfectly simple.

1386
01:06:19,478 --> 01:06:21,309
The doctor does
the examination.

1387
01:06:21,380 --> 01:06:23,041
I make a detailed record.

1388
01:06:23,115 --> 01:06:24,309
I do a dental report.

1389
01:06:24,383 --> 01:06:25,372
Take fingerprints.

1390
01:06:25,450 --> 01:06:27,315
Report on vital organs,
cause of death.

1391
01:06:27,386 --> 01:06:30,822
Ah, you take fingerprints.

1392
01:06:30,889 --> 01:06:34,086
I wonder, would you
mind taking mine?

1393
01:06:34,159 --> 01:06:35,421
What?

1394
01:06:35,494 --> 01:06:38,395
No, you see I'm trying to
understand the process.

1395
01:06:38,463 --> 01:06:40,488
Trying to see if
anything could go wrong.

1396
01:06:40,566 --> 01:06:42,591
Nothing could go wrong.

1397
01:06:42,668 --> 01:06:44,192
Well?

1398
01:06:45,437 --> 01:06:47,371
Very well.

1399
01:06:47,439 --> 01:06:48,497
Thank you.

1400
01:06:55,414 --> 01:06:57,473
You have very warm hands.

1401
01:06:58,951 --> 01:07:00,919
Do you live alone?

1402
01:07:00,986 --> 01:07:03,454
No.

1403
01:07:03,522 --> 01:07:05,285
Only child?

1404
01:07:05,357 --> 01:07:06,517
I have a brother.

1405
01:07:06,592 --> 01:07:08,116
Brother.

1406
01:07:08,193 --> 01:07:09,922
I always wanted a brother.

1407
01:07:09,995 --> 01:07:11,656
Except my dad took
one look at me

1408
01:07:11,730 --> 01:07:14,028
and thought my mother
had suffered enough.

1409
01:07:14,099 --> 01:07:15,293
Yes.

1410
01:07:15,367 --> 01:07:16,459
Nearly finished.

1411
01:07:16,535 --> 01:07:18,867
All right.

1412
01:07:18,937 --> 01:07:19,995
I see, thank you.

1413
01:07:20,072 --> 01:07:23,838
Now then, so what you do
is you fill out this report,

1414
01:07:23,909 --> 01:07:25,137
put it in a file like that,

1415
01:07:25,210 --> 01:07:26,040
Thank you.

1416
01:07:26,111 --> 01:07:27,339
And you send it over to us.

1417
01:07:27,412 --> 01:07:28,379
Is that how it works?

1418
01:07:28,447 --> 01:07:29,778
Yes, one here, one to you.

1419
01:07:29,848 --> 01:07:31,213
I'm not sure I understand you.

1420
01:07:31,283 --> 01:07:33,342
You're saying you lost
the file we sent you?

1421
01:07:33,418 --> 01:07:34,885
Isn't it kept
in police records?

1422
01:07:34,953 --> 01:07:36,648
Well, if it
arrived at my office

1423
01:07:36,722 --> 01:07:38,485
it could have
ended up anywhere.

1424
01:07:38,557 --> 01:07:40,548
Well, then I don't think
you should take ours.

1425
01:07:40,626 --> 01:07:42,526
Oh, all right.

1426
01:07:42,594 --> 01:07:44,528
Well, just make a
copy of that will you

1427
01:07:44,596 --> 01:07:46,291
and send it over to my office.

1428
01:07:46,365 --> 01:07:48,333
Really, Mr. Frost.

1429
01:07:48,400 --> 01:07:50,163
Thank you.

1430
01:07:50,235 --> 01:07:52,965
What do I do with these?

1431
01:07:53,038 --> 01:07:54,801
Oh, I'd put them on file.

1432
01:07:54,873 --> 01:07:56,067
You never know,
save you a job,

1433
01:07:56,141 --> 01:07:58,803
in case I end up
on one of your slabs.

1434
01:08:03,248 --> 01:08:04,579
Jack!

1435
01:08:04,650 --> 01:08:06,174
Been looking for
you everywhere.

1436
01:08:06,251 --> 01:08:09,015
I want a talk about
the Black Farm Murder.

1437
01:08:09,087 --> 01:08:10,554
Come on Sandy,

1438
01:08:10,622 --> 01:08:13,284
you're talking
about eight years ago.

1439
01:08:13,358 --> 01:08:14,347
I'm talking now.

1440
01:08:14,426 --> 01:08:15,290
I warn you, Jack,

1441
01:08:15,360 --> 01:08:16,588
you've got a real
scandal on your hands.

1442
01:08:16,662 --> 01:08:19,028
Our feisty local MP's

1443
01:08:19,097 --> 01:08:22,089
off to see the
Home Secretary.

1444
01:08:22,167 --> 01:08:22,997
Sandy.

1445
01:08:23,068 --> 01:08:26,162
Ferdie Giggs is a small time
crook with a big time mouth

1446
01:08:26,238 --> 01:08:29,230
who can say anything
because he's living in Spain.

1447
01:08:29,308 --> 01:08:31,742
Ferdie would admit to the
Slaughter of the Innocents

1448
01:08:31,810 --> 01:08:33,675
if it meant he could
get a big fat check

1449
01:08:33,745 --> 01:08:34,939
out of one of you lot.

1450
01:08:35,013 --> 01:08:36,947
He says Mrs. Dale hired him

1451
01:08:37,015 --> 01:08:41,247
to kill her husband
for the insurance.

1452
01:08:41,320 --> 01:08:44,517
The Black Farm murder was
an art theft that went wrong.

1453
01:08:44,589 --> 01:08:46,716
Ferdie Giggs wasn't
even there the night

1454
01:08:46,792 --> 01:08:49,124
that Jonathan Dale
was murdered.

1455
01:08:49,194 --> 01:08:50,786
He was there for the
funeral though, wasn't he?

1456
01:08:50,862 --> 01:08:54,923
Newspaper files, Jack.

1457
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:58,401
That's Ferdie Giggs, isn't it?

1458
01:08:58,470 --> 01:08:59,664
And that's Mrs Dale?

1459
01:08:59,738 --> 01:09:02,104
Yes, yes, yes, all right.

1460
01:09:02,174 --> 01:09:05,769
You kept this
file on the case?

1461
01:09:05,844 --> 01:09:06,640
Course.

1462
01:09:06,712 --> 01:09:09,476
That's how
newspapers function.

1463
01:09:09,548 --> 01:09:12,176
You couldn't let me have a
copy of that file could you.

1464
01:09:12,250 --> 01:09:15,378
Over at my office,
as soon as possible?

1465
01:09:15,454 --> 01:09:19,151
Paper co-operates
with re-investigation?

1466
01:09:19,224 --> 01:09:22,455
Or have you just
lost your records?

1467
01:09:26,264 --> 01:09:28,061
My office as soon as possible.

1468
01:09:28,133 --> 01:09:29,657
Thank you, Sandy.

1469
01:09:32,571 --> 01:09:34,732
Possibly in her early forties.

1470
01:09:34,806 --> 01:09:38,105
Quite intelligent
and educated.

1471
01:09:38,176 --> 01:09:40,872
Sunglasses, wearing
a big overcoat.

1472
01:09:40,946 --> 01:09:42,243
And what was the painting?

1473
01:09:42,314 --> 01:09:43,645
I recognized it at once.

1474
01:09:43,715 --> 01:09:44,807
It was a Hockney.

1475
01:09:44,883 --> 01:09:47,215
One of the California
swimming pool series.

1476
01:09:47,285 --> 01:09:50,118
No doubt you asked
about its provenance.

1477
01:09:50,188 --> 01:09:51,780
Yes.

1478
01:09:51,857 --> 01:09:53,552
That was when she said
she didn't want to sell it

1479
01:09:53,625 --> 01:09:55,422
and walked out.

1480
01:09:55,494 --> 01:09:56,483
Hockney?

1481
01:09:56,561 --> 01:09:59,428
Wouldn't that
be really valuable?

1482
01:09:59,498 --> 01:10:03,457
Yes, of course,
a small fortune.

1483
01:10:08,473 --> 01:10:09,599
Mrs. Dale?

1484
01:10:10,709 --> 01:10:11,698
Detective Inspector Frost,

1485
01:10:11,777 --> 01:10:13,938
Denton CID.

1486
01:10:14,012 --> 01:10:16,173
We met about eight years ago.

1487
01:10:16,248 --> 01:10:17,510
Yes, I remember.

1488
01:10:17,582 --> 01:10:19,880
When Jonathan was murdered.

1489
01:10:19,951 --> 01:10:20,975
I have been expecting you.

1490
01:10:21,052 --> 01:10:24,488
Ever since I read that
story about Ferdie Giggs.

1491
01:10:24,556 --> 01:10:27,184
Yeah, that's what I wanted
to talk to you about.

1492
01:10:27,259 --> 01:10:29,989
I'm sorry, but I do
have to ask you this.

1493
01:10:30,061 --> 01:10:32,689
Ferdie Giggs maintains
that you asked him

1494
01:10:32,764 --> 01:10:34,891
to do the killings so
that you could collect

1495
01:10:34,966 --> 01:10:37,025
the insurance money
on the paintings.

1496
01:10:37,102 --> 01:10:40,003
There wasn't any insurance
on the paintings.

1497
01:10:40,071 --> 01:10:42,801
Jonathan never bothered.

1498
01:10:42,874 --> 01:10:44,000
Take a look.

1499
01:10:46,311 --> 01:10:50,213
It's not worth a
killing for, is it?

1500
01:10:50,282 --> 01:10:51,306
No.

1501
01:10:55,720 --> 01:10:57,915
Ferdie was a dealer.

1502
01:10:57,989 --> 01:11:02,551
He sold Jonathan
a few paintings.

1503
01:11:02,627 --> 01:11:04,219
And so Ferdie
tipped off his friends

1504
01:11:04,296 --> 01:11:07,424
that there was something
worth taking at the house.

1505
01:11:07,499 --> 01:11:10,957
but he wasn't
there that night?

1506
01:11:11,036 --> 01:11:12,298
No.

1507
01:11:12,370 --> 01:11:14,099
We'd been away
for the weekend.

1508
01:11:14,172 --> 01:11:15,605
The weather turned bad

1509
01:11:15,674 --> 01:11:18,302
an Jonathan was
worried about his beasts.

1510
01:11:18,376 --> 01:11:20,503
We came home on
the Saturday night

1511
01:11:20,579 --> 01:11:22,604
and there in the house...

1512
01:11:22,681 --> 01:11:24,911
Were two men, right?

1513
01:11:24,983 --> 01:11:26,780
One was Branson.

1514
01:11:26,852 --> 01:11:28,114
Who was the other?

1515
01:11:28,186 --> 01:11:29,483
Well, we never
found out, did we?

1516
01:11:29,554 --> 01:11:33,752
No, because he was wearing
a balaclava over his face.

1517
01:11:33,825 --> 01:11:35,725
But it couldn't have
been Ferdie Giggs,

1518
01:11:35,794 --> 01:11:36,818
he was too tall.

1519
01:11:36,895 --> 01:11:40,194
Exactly.

1520
01:11:40,265 --> 01:11:43,701
So what about your
husband's paintings?

1521
01:11:43,768 --> 01:11:46,669
One of them was
quite valuable, was it?

1522
01:11:46,738 --> 01:11:49,002
You mean the David Hockney.

1523
01:11:49,074 --> 01:11:50,336
Yes.

1524
01:11:50,408 --> 01:11:52,205
Yes, his brother
gave it to him.

1525
01:11:52,277 --> 01:11:54,973
He said he'd been given
it by Hockney himself.

1526
01:11:55,046 --> 01:11:57,310
Jonathan never
insured that either.

1527
01:11:57,382 --> 01:12:03,252
It went in the robbery,
and that was that.

1528
01:12:03,321 --> 01:12:05,346
Did you know it was
offered for sale yesterday.

1529
01:12:05,423 --> 01:12:07,391
At the Ansty Gallery.

1530
01:12:07,459 --> 01:12:08,983
You've found it then?

1531
01:12:09,060 --> 01:12:10,027
No.

1532
01:12:10,095 --> 01:12:13,064
It was offered for
sale by a woman.

1533
01:12:13,131 --> 01:12:15,759
Oh, and you thought it was me.

1534
01:12:15,834 --> 01:12:17,631
It wasn't.

1535
01:12:17,702 --> 01:12:19,533
No, well I did wonder,

1536
01:12:19,604 --> 01:12:24,701
but I don't
believe it was you.

1537
01:12:24,776 --> 01:12:29,611
Did you know a man called
Leslie Jackson, an Australian?

1538
01:12:29,681 --> 01:12:30,739
No, I didn't.

1539
01:12:30,815 --> 01:12:33,579
Should I have done?

1540
01:12:33,652 --> 01:12:36,746
No, it was just a thought.

1541
01:12:36,821 --> 01:12:40,655
Well, thank you
very much Mrs. Dale.

1542
01:12:40,725 --> 01:12:44,456
Does this mean I might
get the paintings back?

1543
01:12:44,529 --> 01:12:46,554
I don't know.

1544
01:12:46,631 --> 01:12:47,689
I'm sorry.

1545
01:12:47,766 --> 01:12:49,700
I honestly don't know.

1546
01:13:20,365 --> 01:13:21,457
Something for me?

1547
01:13:21,533 --> 01:13:22,056
Yeah.

1548
01:13:22,133 --> 01:13:23,896
Miss Grey brought this
over from the path lab,

1549
01:13:23,969 --> 01:13:25,766
said you've to be more
careful with it this time.

1550
01:13:25,837 --> 01:13:26,667
Oh, thank you.

1551
01:13:26,738 --> 01:13:28,467
Oh, and this stuff
just came over

1552
01:13:28,540 --> 01:13:30,838
from the Denton Evening Echo,

1553
01:13:30,909 --> 01:13:31,603
and Jack?

1554
01:13:31,676 --> 01:13:32,404
Yes?

1555
01:13:32,477 --> 01:13:33,341
Mullett wants to see you.

1556
01:13:33,411 --> 01:13:34,469
And he won't take
no for an answer.

1557
01:13:34,546 --> 01:13:36,741
Good, cos I can't
wait to see him.

1558
01:13:36,815 --> 01:13:38,680
I will.

1559
01:13:38,750 --> 01:13:40,115
I will.

1560
01:13:40,185 --> 01:13:41,447
Yes, I will dear.

1561
01:13:42,887 --> 01:13:43,876
Yes, dear.

1562
01:13:48,793 --> 01:13:49,725
Well?

1563
01:13:51,096 --> 01:13:52,757
I thought you wanted
to see me, sir.

1564
01:13:52,831 --> 01:13:54,230
You know I do, yes.

1565
01:14:02,841 --> 01:14:03,830
Now I'm being interviewed

1566
01:14:03,908 --> 01:14:06,468
for the post of Assistant
Chief Constable on Wednesday.

1567
01:14:06,544 --> 01:14:09,672
And very good
luck to you, sir.

1568
01:14:09,748 --> 01:14:11,375
No doubt some
people in this station

1569
01:14:11,449 --> 01:14:12,973
would be pleased to
see the back of me.

1570
01:14:13,051 --> 01:14:14,245
Oh, no.

1571
01:14:14,319 --> 01:14:17,720
In which case I'd appreciate
a good deal more co-operation.

1572
01:14:17,789 --> 01:14:19,086
Everything in
this station's fine

1573
01:14:19,157 --> 01:14:20,749
except for three
outstanding problems

1574
01:14:20,825 --> 01:14:22,315
every one to do with you.

1575
01:14:22,394 --> 01:14:24,157
You're not referring
to my petrol expenses,

1576
01:14:24,229 --> 01:14:26,026
are you, sir?

1577
01:14:28,066 --> 01:14:29,090
Thank you very much,

1578
01:14:29,167 --> 01:14:31,067
but that's not
what I meant, no.

1579
01:14:31,136 --> 01:14:34,037
What about the
Black Farm Murder?

1580
01:14:34,105 --> 01:14:36,039
Yes, here's the file.

1581
01:14:36,107 --> 01:14:38,098
Sorry it took so long.

1582
01:14:49,921 --> 01:14:53,220
They're just
newspaper cuttings.

1583
01:14:53,291 --> 01:14:54,485
Yes.

1584
01:14:54,559 --> 01:14:57,084
But we've nearly
settled the case.

1585
01:14:57,162 --> 01:15:00,461
Ferdie Giggs was lying.

1586
01:15:00,532 --> 01:15:03,524
He was only after a
Fleet Street handout.

1587
01:15:03,601 --> 01:15:06,263
He never was at the
scene of the crime.

1588
01:15:06,337 --> 01:15:08,703
We've also managed to trace

1589
01:15:08,773 --> 01:15:11,173
a number of the
Black Farm paintings.

1590
01:15:11,242 --> 01:15:15,338
Trouble is, they were in the
hands of Lester Bryce-Jones.

1591
01:15:15,413 --> 01:15:17,574
The victim at the
Riverside Apartments.

1592
01:15:17,649 --> 01:15:21,585
But, he does seem to be
linked with the Appendix Man,

1593
01:15:21,653 --> 01:15:25,453
so, one investigation
leads to another.

1594
01:15:25,523 --> 01:15:28,048
We should have this
all cleared up in,

1595
01:15:28,126 --> 01:15:30,560
well you know,
no time at all.

1596
01:15:30,628 --> 01:15:32,926
By Wednesday?

1597
01:15:32,997 --> 01:15:35,090
Wednesday?

1598
01:15:35,166 --> 01:15:37,134
Yes, probably Wednesday, yes.

1599
01:15:37,202 --> 01:15:40,535
Well, that's excellent.

1600
01:15:40,605 --> 01:15:41,435
Good.

1601
01:15:41,506 --> 01:15:42,598
Thank you, sir.

1602
01:15:44,776 --> 01:15:47,336
Oh, there is one small thing

1603
01:15:47,412 --> 01:15:49,073
that you could help me with.

1604
01:15:49,147 --> 01:15:51,741
I need an exhumation order.

1605
01:15:51,816 --> 01:15:53,215
Who for?

1606
01:15:53,284 --> 01:15:54,717
Well, I don't know his name.

1607
01:15:54,786 --> 01:15:55,980
He's the Appendix Man.

